<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Calls for Peaceful Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
Sunday called for Arab and Muslim countries to solve disputes by
peaceful means in order to pave the way for economic development
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah made the appeal during his meeting with visiting
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi, who arrived in Amman
Saturday on a three-day fence mending visit.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Abdullah said Jordan exerted efforts to
remove the causes of tension and to enable people in the region to
pay closer attention to economic growth and development.
</P>
<P>
He said that conflicts in the region should be settled by
peaceful means and reconciliation, and Jordan fully supports
conflict-preventive diplomacy in the Arab and Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah did not refer directly to the disputes between Iran
and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) over three Gulf islands, Abu
Musa, the Greater and Lesser Tunbs.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here said the UAE has asked Jordan to mediate
over the disputes during Kharrazi's visit.
</P>
<P>
However, after talks with his Jordanian counterpart Abdel-Ilah
al-Khatib on Saturday, Kharrazi said Iran rejected any outside
mediation over the dispute with the UAE over the islands.
</P>
<P>
He termed the dispute as a "bilateral issue" which Iran
preferred to solve directly with the UAE, and said he did not
raise the issue during his talks with al-Khatib.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's ties with Iran remained sour since the 1980s as
Amman sided with Baghdad during the eight-year war between Iran
and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been drastically
improved since last month when Abdullah invited Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami to visit Amman.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has accepted the invitation, but has not set a
date to visit the desert kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
