<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Marks Africa Refugee Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Civil conflicts in Africa which
have forced people to flee for their lives are the result of
intolerance, poor governance, clamor for power and greed, a senior
official of the U.N. High Commissioner

for Refugees (UNHCR) has said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering here Sunday to commemorate the 30th
anniversary of the Africa Refugee Day, Yvette Stevens, the UNHCR
representative to Kenya, said civil conflicts have expanded the
population of refugees in Africa from one million in 1969 to some
seven million at present.
</P>
<P>
"Civil strife still plague the continent with some 14 countries
at war, which still continue to produce large numbers of refugees
and displaced persons," she noted.
</P>
<P>
While the rest of the world moved ahead, Africa would
retrogress, she said, adding African leaders should preach
tolerance not division; the interest of countries rather than
individuals should take precedence. Only then would one ensure a
safe and happy environment for all.
</P>
<P>
Stevens said most of the arms used in Africa were imported
outside the continent, and appealed to the international
community to declare embargoes on arms import in some African
countries.
</P>
<P>
On the refugee problems in Africa, she said, the UNHCR would
have a role to play in making the lives of refugees more tolerable
and even in resolving the root causes of conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Shariff Nassir, Kenyan Minister for Home
Affairs, National Heritage, Culture and Social Services, said the
global refugee population had passed the 21 million mark, one
third of which had been produced by Africa.
</P>
<P>
There were some 200,000 refugees in Kenya, he said, adding: "we
have seen the interference to all aspects of life by the refugees
and have seen the over-stretching of our resources and also the
security risks posed by our "guests", especially in the areas
bordering the refugee producing countries.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the refugees in Kenya are mainly from Sudan,
Somalia, Eritrea and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on Refugees was signed in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia,
by 34 African countries in 1969 and so far 46 nations have signed
the convention.
</P>
<P>
According to UNHCR statistics, Guinea is the largest host of
refugees, taking in more than 413,000, Sudan 319,500, Tanzania
343,900 and Ethiopia 262,000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sierra Leone is the biggest source of refugees with
409,900, to be followed by Somalia with 401,300, Sudan 372,900,
Eritrea 342,300 and Burundi 299,400. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
