<HEADLINE> Jordan Hopes to Improve ties with Iran: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Raouf Rawabdeh said Sunday his country hoped to build up
brotherly ties with Iran on the basis of mutual respect and
non-interference in internal affairs of each country.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during his meeting with Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi, the highest-ranking Iranian official to
visit Jordan in more than a decade on a ground-breaking mission.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh said Iran enjoyed a special position among Jordan`s
Islamic brothers, and Amman looked forward to brotherly, friendly
and cooperative ties with Tehran on basis of mutual interests
and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Jordanian prime minister also encouraged
Iranian investors and entrepreneurs to launch joint ventures in
the kingdom as part of the efforts to strengthen bilateral
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Iran was willing to deepen its ties with Jordan
and overcome obstacles impeding their progress and development.
</P>
<P>
Tehran was ready to provide expertise for Amman to help
develop the infrastructure and service projects in the kingdom,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi arrived in Amman Saturday on a three-day fence
mending visit which was expected to end the strains of bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Jordan`s ties with Iran remained sour since the 1980s as Amman
sided with Baghdad during the eight-year war between Iran and
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been drastically
improved since May 1999 when Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
invited Iranian President Mohmmad Khatami to visit Amman.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has accepted the invitation, but has not set a date
to visit the desert kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
