<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Egyptian Veteran Dies at 78 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Former vice president of Egypt Kamal
El-din Hussein, one of the army officers who helped Gamal Abdel
Nasser topple Egypt's monarchy in 1952, has died at the age of 78.
</P>
<P>
Egypt on Sunday held a state funeral for Hussein, who died on
Saturday after a long illness and complications from liver cancer,
the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Hussein joined Nasser in the "free officers" group during the
1948 war with Israel. When the officers overthrew the monarchy
four years later, he became a member of the ruling Revolutionary
Command Council and minister of social affairs.
</P>
<P>
He later was named one of Nasser's many deputies and headed the
National Guard during the 1956 war against Britain and France
following Egypt's nationalization of the Suez Canal.
</P>
<P>
Hussein fell out with Nasser when he opposed many of the late
president's policies, especially his heavy-handed style of
governing and favoritism.
</P>
<P>
Hussein went to the United States three times for treatment
after he was diagnosed with liver cancer several years ago.
</P>
<P>
Hussein, who is survived by his wife, three sons and several
grandchildren, was buried in Benha, his hometown in the Nile
Delta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
