<HEADLINE> Arab League Contacts Arab FMs on Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said on Sunday that the league is consulting with
Arab countries on the idea of holding an Arab summit.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Slovenian Prime
Minister Janez Drnovsek before he ended a three-day visit to
Egypt, Abdel-Meguid said the league is holding contacts with Arab
foreign ministers and permanent representatives to the league to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Following the victory of moderate leader of Israel's Labor
Party Ehud Barak in the country's elections last month, Arabs have
been talking about convening a summit to coordinate and forge a
united stance on the peace talks with Israel's new government
under the prime minister-elect.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak proposed with Moroccan King
Hassan II during a recent visit to the North African country that
a pan-Arab summit be held to discuss the Middle East peace process
and keys issues related to the Arab world. Several Arab countries
have expressed positive response to the call.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid called for full preparations for and consultations
on the possible summit in an effort to guarantee a success and
help restore Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Underlining Arab League's welcome to the call for a summit, the
league chief said the 22-nation pan-Arab forum is interested in
every Arab effort leading to the unification of Arab ranks.
</P>
</TEXT>
