<HEADLINE> Chirac Expresses Concern About Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Sunday expressed grave concern about the situation in Cyprus, the
Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the close of a three-day G-8
summit in Cologne, Germany, Chirac said that not much progress has
been made towards the resolution of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Eight (G-8) compromises the United States, Canada,
Britain, France, Germany, Japan, Italy and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that "the situation in Cyprus is of great concern,
especially in view of Cyprus' candidacy for EU accession."
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation European Union (EU) "does not wish to import any
important conflicts, it wants them resolved beforehand," said
Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the
island through a bi-zonal, bi-communal federation formula, but so
far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
