<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Conflict, Priority for S. Africa's New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Newly appointed South African
Foreign Minister Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma said Sunday that she saw
the conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) one of her
top priorities.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini-Zuma, who was health minister in former president
Nelson Mandela' s cabinet, was speaking on the SABC television's
News maker program.
</P>
<P>
She said unless the conflict in Africa was resolved there was
no possibility of a renaissance on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Although the latest initiative to bring about peace in the DRC
was being led by Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, South Africa
was giving the process its full support, said the foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
"We would like a cease-fire in the DRC and a standstill of
foreign troops, and (to see) the Congolese beginning a meaningful
dialog to resolve the problems there," she said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was involved in talks with all the countries
involved in the Great Lakes conflict including the warring parties
in the DRC, Dlamini- Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
An interview with new Deputy President Jacob Zuma last week was
also broadcast during the News maker program. Jacob Zuma is
Nkosazana Dlamini- Zuma's ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
When asked about reports that the deputy presidency was offered
to Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi, Zuma
said he knew nothing about the issue except what he had read in
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Many people seemed to have mistaken the African National
Congress's (ANC' s) willingness to cooperate with the IFP as a
planned merger between the two parties. However, he said, this had
never been the intention, and the two parties were continuing to
cooperate without considering a merger.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation in KwaZulu-Natal, he said he was
optimistic that the conflict between the ANC and the IFP had been
resolved. He said this was shown by the ease with which the
coalition was formed in the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
"I think we could confidently say that we are past the stage
where the problems of KwaZulu-Natal could slip into a state of
chaos," Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
He said he was convinced that the commitment by the parties to
peace in the province was such that development could not take
place without. 
</P>
</TEXT>
