<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Pledges to Push Cyprus Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said Sunday he will do everything he can to push forward the peace
process in Cyprus, the Cyprus News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the G-8 summit in Cologne, Germany, Blair said
"we will do everything we can to push the process forward" in the
context of the European Union (EU) and the Group of Eight (G-8).
</P>
<P>
Blair pointed out that the G-8 backing for moving the peace
process forward is supportive of other moves to reconcile the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
"All we can do in the G-8 is to give our support to the moves
that are made to reconcile the two communities," he said.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 leaders, in a final statement, urged
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to invite Greek and Turkish
Cypriot leaders for negotiations in the fall.
</P>
<P>
It also called for leaders of the two parties in Cyprus to
commit themselves to negotiating without preconditions on all
issues until a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led international community has been trying for
decades to reunite the island through a bi-zonal, bi-communal
federation formula, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 groups the United States, Canada, Britain, France,
Italy, Germany, Japan and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
