<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Urges India, Pakistan to End Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Sunday called on India
and Pakistan to exercise self-restraint and solve their disputes
through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made at a weekly cabinet session chaired by
Crown Prince and Prime Minister Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah, the
Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait "followed up with concern the military escalation
between India and Pakistan and the serious threat that such
escalation could pose to the safety and security of both
countries," said Information Minister Yusef Mohammad Al-Sumait
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait appealed to both sides to exercise self-restraint and to
resort to negotiations to solve all pending issues through
peaceful means, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
On May 26, India began to pound with heavy artillery and air
strikes "infiltrators" it said backed by Pakistan's armed forces
in the disputed Kashmir region, sharply raising tensions on the
nuclear-armed subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
Heavy casualties and damages have been reported on both sides
following artillery shelling and fierce fightings.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic efforts, both bilateral and international, have so
far failed to reduce the tension between the two long-time foes.
</P>
</TEXT>
