<HEADLINE> Greece Calls for Centralized System of Food Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Greece's Agriculture Minister
George Anomeritis on Sunday urged Europe to establish a
centralized system of food controls in order to protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal in Serres, northern Greece while commenting
on contamination scares in Belgium and the Netherlands, the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that there were actually many problems in the
food chain, but the laboratories and methods and the scientific
staff of the Greek food industry were aiming for the best in terms
of the final product.
</P>
<P>
The Veterinary Department of the Aristotelian University in
northern Thessaloniki said Saturday that Greek meat, milk, eggs
and fish were free of the cancer-producing dioxin found in
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The department called on the Greek Agriculture Ministry to
upgrade its own veterinary division and use other resources in order
to carry out more frequent and efficient controls on food from
livestock rearing through to the end product. 
</P>
