<HEADLINE> EDS-Update with more details Japan-Russia Peace Treaty to Be Concluded Before 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOGNE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Japan and Russia will conclude a
peace treaty before the year 2000, Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi announced here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi made the remark after meeting with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin in Cologne where the Group of Eight (G8) summit had
just ended.
</P>
<P>
During the bilateral talks, Yeltsin said that he would fulfill
the historical tasks of solving the territorial dispute and
signing the peace treaty with Japan as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo and Moscow issued a joint declaration in 1956, ending the
state of war between them. However, Russia's occupation of the
southern Kuril islands, known to Japanese as their "northern
territories" has prevented the two countries from signing a formal
peace treaty and embarking on full economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said that Japan will continue its support to Russia for
disposing nuclear weapons and provide funds in this regard.
</P>
