<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB to Further Help Tanzania Solve Debt Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will continue
to assist Tanzania in solving the debt problem so that the
country's economy could develop at a faster pace, a senior bank
official said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Although Tanzania did not get debt relief at a G-8 summit in
Germany earlier this week, the country does have a debt problem,
World Bank Managing Director and Corporate Secretary Shengman
Zhang told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the World Bank will take measures to alleviate
external debt for Tanzania and that a plan on reducing the
country's commercial debts is being studied. However, he declined
to give details.
</P>
<P>
Burdened with an external debt of around eight billion U.S.
dollars, Tanzania has seen education and health services
deteriorating in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Despite these problems, Tanzania's macro-economic situation has
become stable after years of reform, the bank official said before
leaving for Uganda to continue his African tour.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania has basically discovered a good reform path," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang praised the rapid development of tourism and mining
during the course of reform, but said the industry sector still
needs to increase its shares in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania's industry is still not fully developed as the sector
 contributes only 15 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP),
a rate which is too low," he said.
</P>
<P>
To accelerate economic development, Tanzania needs to adhere to
 reforms, improve management, expand the private sector, as well
as improve infrastructure, education and health services, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the past four days, the World Bank managing director has
met top leaders of Tanzania, financial figures and private
businessmen. He also toured World Bank-funded projects in various
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The visit, he said, is to learn the situation of Tanzania and
enhance understanding with the government on what to do next.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has actively supported Tanzania's economic
development efforts through more than 130 bank-financed projects
since the 1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
