<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D'Alema Says Italian Deficit to Come Down by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema said Sunday that Italy's deficit would be lowered to 1.5
percent of GDP by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency ANSA, D'Alema, who is being
present at the Group of Eight economic summit in Cologne of
Germany, said that the deficit target would be reached through a
combination of spending cuts and the easing of Italy's high level
of fiscal pressure, adding that the government was committed to
lowering the amount of taxes paid by low-income families.
</P>
<P>
At the end of May, Italy won permission from other euro-zone
nations to let its 1999 deficit rise to 2.4 percent of GDP from
the agreed 2 percent because of slack economic growth.
</P>
<P>
This decision unleashed a wave of criticism, with some
commentators claiming it represented the first crack in the
monetary union's Stability Pact, and that it was responsible for
the recent weakness of euro.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema went on to say that "no serious analyst would link the
easing of Italy's deficit-GDP ratio to the presumed difficulties
of the euro."
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to appeal to national pride on the issue, because
that's a rare phenomenon in Italy," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that other euro-zone countries might have to follow the
same course as Italy and "some were pleased that Italy clarified
things. It could pave the way for others to do the same."
</P>
<P>
"We asked for our targets to be re-set on the basis of economic
realities," the premier concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
