<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demand for Natural Gas to Grow in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The demand for natural gas in
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will grow substantially and far
outstrip supply in years to come, according to a recent study.
</P>
<P>
The study, published in the latest issue of Nicosia-based
Middle East Economic Survey, indicated that daily demand for
natural gas in the UAE was projected to grow from 2.6 billion
cubic feet (about 80 million cubic meters) in 1998 to 5.1 billion
cubic feet (about 150 million cubic meters) in 2005 and 6.1
billion cubic feet (about 180 million cubic meters) in 2010.
</P>
<P>
Although natural gas supply in the UAE will also increase, the
study said demand will far outstrip supply, opening the door for
over 2.1 billion cubic feet (60 million cubic meters) of daily
imports by 2005, growing to 3 billion cubic feet (90 million cubic
meters) by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The figures for estimated natural gas demand excluded a plant
at Das Island, which utilizes some 1.2 billion cubic feet (40
million cubic meters) of natural gas daily to produce liquefied
natural gas for export.
</P>
<P>
The figures also excluded a gas condensate recycling project,
due on stream in 2000, which involves recycling some 825 million
cubic feet (24.8 million cubic meters) of wet gas daily to
produce condensate, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that daily supply of natural gas in the UAE
in 1998 was 2.27 billion cubic feet (about 68.1 million cubic
meters). The figure is expected to go up to 2.99 billion cubic
feet (89.7 million cubic meters) in 2005 and 3.07 billion cubic
feet (92.1 million cubic meters) in the year 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Police Make Further Arrest in Omagh Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Police in the Irish Republic said
on Monday they had arrested another man in connection with last
year's bombing at Omagh, bringing to 11 the number being
questioned on both sides of the Irish border since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The arrest was made in the border town of Dundalk, County Louth
late Monday morning, a BBC report said.
</P>
<P>
The latest suspect was in his mid-20s, and was taken for
questioning, the report quoted a police source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Six men were detained following raids on Sunday morning, while
in Northern Ireland four men were arrested in the border area of
South Armagh.
</P>
<P>
Local Irish media reports said all those men were linked to the
Real IRA, the dissident republican faction responsible for the
bomb attack on August 15 last year in the market town of Omagh,
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The bomb killed 29 people outright and injured more than 200,
making it the single worst atrocity in Northern Ireland's
sectarian conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Real IRA, which aimed to derail the British-ruled
province's fragile peace process with the attack, was faced with
security crackdown and public outrage after the attack. The group
called off hostilities soon after the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The main republican guerrilla group, the Irish Republican Army,
declared a ceasefire in its war against British rule in July 1997,
paving the way for last year's Good Friday peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Police on both sides of the border have arrested and released
several suspects in connection with the Omagh bombing over the
last few months. Only one man has been charged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Declares December 31 Bank Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS) has decided that December 31 of this year will be
bank holiday, MAS Managing Director Koh Yong Guan said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Koh told those attending the 26th Annual Dinner of the
Association of Banks in Singapore (ABS) that the MAS has accepted
the ABS' proposal to declare December 31 a bank holiday.
</P>
<P>
Billing the announcement as part of the MAS' year 2000 efforts,
Koh said this will enable banks to begin their year-end processing
and back-ups early so that these activities are completed in time
for the new year.
</P>
<P>
According to the MAS, a bank holiday is not a public holiday
and it entails:
</P>
<P>
-- Closure of bank branches on December 31, 1999. Bank
customers, however, can still use existing 24-hour banking
services such as ATMs, phone banking and Internet banking.
</P>
<P>
-- A non-settlement day on December 31, 1999. This means that
financial transactions scheduled for settlement on December 31,
1999, will either be brought forward to December 30, 1999, or
postponed to January 3, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Koh announced that Singapore International Monetary
Exchange has recently decided to launch a Singapore dollar
interest rate future contact.
</P>
<P>
This will give investors and financial intermediaries another
instrument to manage their interest rate risks and help promote
greater liquidity in the Singapore dollar bond and derivatives
markets.
</P>
<P>
Koh also urged local banks to seize the opportunities presented
by the Internet and expand their Internet banking capability and
learn from the experience of leading international banks in
managing the disintermediation process and meeting the challenges
posed by the emergence of the capital market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
