<HEADLINE> Vancouver Warns of Child Prostitution Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Canada's western province of
British Columbia is seeing a boom in child prostitution as a
result of lax enforcement of federal laws, said a Vancouver
social agency Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of children are being used as prostitutes in British
Columbia, largely because the province has failed to do an
effective job in enforcing the federal child prostitution law, the
agency said in its report carried by the newspaper here.
</P>
<P>
Vancouver's Downtown Eastside Youth Activities Society called
child prostitution "an organized growth industry" in the province,
where Vancouver, a major city, is seeing its third generation of
sex trade workers in the same family.
</P>
<P>
The province lags far behind several other provinces such as
Quebec in law enforcement, the report said.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 transactions occur each day in Vancouver
involving the purchase of a child and "there are no barriers to it,
" the report added.
</P>
<P>
The country's federal law forbids buying or attempting to buy
sex from a person under 18. From April 1, 1997, to March 31, 1998,
20 charges were brought under the federal child prostitution law
in British Columbia, compared with 41 charges in Ontario and 67 in
Quebec in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Strict law enforcement has helped Quebec keep child
prostitution under control, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
