<HEADLINE> Iraq Requests UN to Stop U.S. Spy Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Monday requested
that the United Nations intervene in U.S. spying activities in the
country so as to bring a halt to this practice in the interests of
safeguarding the reputation of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Iraq's
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz said the United states was
persisting in its unlawful and immoral interference in Iraq's
international affairs by sending agents of its intelligence
services who used the U.N. agencies working in Iraq as a cover
for their activities as spies.
</P>
<P>
"At other times, it sends agents through northern Iraq to
infiltrate the country in order to carry out acts of espionage
and sabotage," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
"The persistence of the United States Administration in
blatantly interfering in Iraq internal affairs and its use of
the United Nations agencies as a cover for its interference is
a flagrant violation of the spirit and letter of the Charter of
the United Nations and of the norms and percepts of
international law," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It constitutes an attempt to destroy the reputation of the
United Nations as an international organization together with
the good name of its personnel, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy Prime Minister requested the U.N. chief that he
intervene to ensure the representatives and personnel of the
United Nations agencies and bodies do not cooperate with these
spies and informers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
