<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. to Set up "Early Warning System" for Internal Quarrels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 21 Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and the United
States will set up an "early warning system" to prevent internal
disputes from escalating into conflicts and ruining their overall
ties, their joint statement issued here Monday said.
</P>
<P>
The statement was signed by US President Bill Clinton, German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and acting European Commission
President Jacques Santer, following the EU-US summit on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During their three-hour meeting, the three leaders agreed to
set up two working groups responsible for political and trade
issues, and to coordinate the so-called "trans-Atlantic
relationship."
</P>
<P>
Under the "early warning system," the interests of the EU and
the US will be taken into account by drawing up political
principles and legal and administrative regulations, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also demanded better communication and more
transparency in the system.
</P>
<P>
The Bonn summit, following the three-day Group of Eight (G-8)
summit in Cologne, focused primarily on two topics, funding Balkan
reconstruction and diffusing EU-US disputes, especially in the
area of trade.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the United States and the 15-member EU have
been quarreling bitterly over a series of trade problems,
including the banana dispute and the hormone-treated U.S. beef.
</P>
<P>
"Too often in the past President Clinton and I have had to
spend time on damaging disputes, even if 98 percent of our trade
is trouble free," Santer said at a press conference after the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
