<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's Telecom Sector Sees Appreciable Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's telecom sector has seen
appreciable development in the past two decades and its service
quality is among the best in the South Asian region, a telecom
official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bala Ram Pradhananga, deputy general manager of the
government-owned Nepal Telecommunications Corporation (NTC), told
Xinhua in an interview that when the NTC was established in 1975,
telecom development in Nepal was only in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
"However, accelerated development in this sector has taken
place since then," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pradhananga said the number of telephone subscribers has
increased from 7,000 in 1975 to more than 210,000 at present and
the installed capacity from 10,000 lines to 250,000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the average telephone density has increased from a
meager 0.08 per 100 people to one, he said.
</P>
<P>
Now all the 75 district headquarters are linked through
reliable telecom services and about 1,700 of the 3,912
village-level administrative units or village development
committees have access to modern telephone facilities, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that for rural areas there are systems like
point-to-point system VHF and UHF and digital multiple radio
access systems (MARTS) and satellite-based systems (VSAT) have
been deployed.
</P>
<P>
"The NTC's switching and transmission networks were fully
digitized in 1998," he said. "Now 131 countries can be reached
through IDD (international direct dialing) facilities provided by
the NTC."
</P>
<P>
Recently, the NTC launched the GSM (global system for mobile
communications) cellular mobile telephone system in Kathmandu and
is now extending it to three other major cities in the country,
the deputy general manager said.
</P>
<P>
On the NTC's future plans, he disclosed that the NTC has
completed the internal process to install pay phone service in a
few major cities in the kingdom in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The NTC also plans to introduce Internet gateway access in the
near future to help Internet service providers provide better
Internet services and set up a satellite-based trunk network
linking Kathmandu and other major cities to increase the
reliability of the telecom services, Pradhananga said.
</P>
<P>
"The NTC has deployed optical fiber cables in the trunk network
of the Kathmandu Valley and is planning for an east-west optical
network to link the eastern and western parts of Nepal," he added.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunication services available now in Nepal include
local telephone service, national trunk telephone service,
international trunk telephone service, bureau fax service, telex
service, national and international leased service, mobile service
and telegraph service.
</P>
<P>
Private operators are providing other value-added services like
Internet service, E-mail service, voice-mail service and
fax-to-fax service, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pradhananga said his country was the first in the South Asian
region to introduce digital switching technology in the early
1980s and the quality of service is among the best in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the telecom sector accounts for an estimated
1.28 percent of the country's gross domestic product in the
current 1998/99 fiscal year as against 1.21 percent in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
New targets have been set under the country's sixth telecom
development project (1997-2002), which includes the provision of
telephone services in all major cities, the increase of telephone
density to at least 2.5 percent and the provision of at least one
public-call office in 1,800 more village development committees,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, telephone exchanges will be installed in all
district headquarters and major commercial centers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The NTC has experienced some constraints in the development of
the telecom sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited the lack of financial resources, trained and skilled
manpower and infrastructure like roads and power, brain drain of
experienced employees, high cost of deployment and maintenance of
telephone services in mountainous rural areas, inadequacy of
coordination among government agencies and inflexible rules,
regulations and procedures.
</P>
<P>
He believes that the private sector's involvement will help
boost the development process. With the enactment of the New
Telecommunication Act 1997, the government has given its
commitment to liberalizing the telecom sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Although lately only some value-added services have been open
to private operators, it can be expected that basic services may
be open for competition in the future," Pradhananga said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Gets New Official SEA Games Accreditation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- New Philippine Olympic Committee (
POC) president Celso Dayrit has secured an official accreditation
for the Philippine team to participate in the forthcoming Brunei
Southeast Asian Games (SEA Games).
</P>
<P>
The accreditation and invitation from the Brunei Committee and
SEA Games Federation president Prince Haji Sufri Bulkiah is now
taken as a seal of legitimacy for Dayrit's new POC administration.
</P>
<P>
Philippine chief de mission to the SEA Games Sultan Jamalul
Kiram went to Brunei last weekend to secure the official
invitation, the same document which the SEA Games Federation
issued to ousted POC president Cristy Ramos last March 8.
</P>
<P>
"We have to provide our own accreditation because it seems
Cristy won't give to us the first official invitation issued by
the SEA Games Federation. At least we are now officially
accredited," Dayrit said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dayrit assumed as POC president early this month using a
temporary office after the International Olympic Committee
recognized the extraordinary general assembly meeting last May 10
where Ramos was ousted through a majority vote of no confidence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kiram said that host Brunei is doing well in its
preparation for the regional biennial event which will be held in
this tiny but oil-rich country for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to reports that participating athletes and officials
from 12 countries will find difficulty in booking hotel
accommodations, Kiram said Brunei has constructed 7-story and 350-
room building for each country not to mention the 3,000-seater
dining hall for the delegates.
</P>
<P>
Some 250 Filipino athletes will be competing in 19 of the 22
sports calendared in this year biennial event on August 7-15.
</P>
</TEXT>
