<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Supports G-8 Statement on Cyprus Issue: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth
Brill Monday expressed the U.S. support for the statement on
Cyprus adopted by the G-8 summit in Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides, Brill said the statement underscores the interest of
the leading countries of the world to resume a comprehensive
negotiating process on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Brill said the U.S. endorses this, adding that "we look
forward to moving forward."
</P>
<P>
At the Cologne summit which ended Sunday, the G-8 urged
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to invite both sides in Cyprus
for talks this autumn, noting that such negotiations should take
full consideration of relevant U.N. resolutions and treaties on
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
They also called on leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sides to commit themselves to negotiating without preconditions on
all issues and to commit themselves to negotiations until a
settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-zonal, bi-communal federation, but so far no
tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 groups the United States, Canada, Britain, France,
Italy, Germany, Japan and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus: No Comment on G-8 Statement on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government Monday said
it would not at present comment on the G-8 statement relating to
the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Government Spokesman Costas Serezis said the government would
wait until a U.N. resolution calling on the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides in Cyprus to resume negotiations is approved later
this month.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 summit which ended Sunday in Cologne, Germany, urged
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan "in accordance with relevant
U.N. Security Council resolutions to invite the leaders of the two
parties to negotiations in the fall of 1999."
</P>
<P>
The G-8 leaders, in their final statement, also urged leaders
of the two parties to commit themselves to the principles of no
pre-conditions during the negotiations, all issues to be on the
table, full consideration of relevant U.N. resolutions and
treaties, and to continue negotiating until a settlement is
reached.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led international community has been trying for
decades to reunite the island through a bi-zonal, bi-communal
federation formula, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 groups the United States, Canada, Britain, France,
Italy, Germany, Japan and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
