<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Suffers "Diplomatic Setback" on Kashmir: Pak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has been seeing a "most
serious diplomatic setback" for its arch-rival India as a G-8
statement urged India to resume dialogue with Pakistan on the
Kashmir crisis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news briefing here Monday, spokesman for the
Pakistani Foreign Office Rafiq Altaf said India has suffered its
most serious diplomatic setback as its efforts for endorsement of
its stand by the Group of Eight countries (G-8) have been
rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, India has also explained the G-8 statement as
favorable to itself as the statement called for an end to
"infiltration" in the disputed area of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
India blamed Pakistan for the so-called "infiltrators" in the
Kargil sector near the Line of Control (LoC), which was denied by
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
According to Altaf, India was "begging" the international
community, particularly the G-8, to endorse India's continued
military action against the Mujahideen and reject recourse to
dialogue and peaceful negotiations as suggested by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"The international community has seen through India's antics,"
said the spokesman, adding, "The G-8, instead, categorically
upheld Pakistan's position that the hostilities in Kashmir should
be halted, the Line of Control (LoC) mutually respected and the
dialogue resumed for a peaceful solution."
</P>
<P>
The G-8 said, "Any military action to change the status quo is
irresponsible," Altaf noted, stressing that Pakistan is not trying
to change the LoC.
</P>
<P>
He went on to blame India for its violations of the LoC in
Chorbat La in 1972, Siachen in 1984 and Qamar in 1988 and its
current artillery ground attacks against Pakistan posts along the
LoC and its "aerial incursions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
