<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Trade Opportunities Between China, Latin America (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Eight experts from Latin America
said here today that trade between that continent and China should
go beyond mere exchanges of raw materials and primary products.
</P>
<P>
They made the remark here today at an economic and trade
seminar between China and Latin America, including the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that a delegation of officials from
several Latin American countries had explained to the Chinese
people the overall economic situation in Latin America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Juan Carlos Moneta, permanent secretary of the Latin American
Economic System (also known as SELA), said Latin America had
experienced economic recovery before being deeply influenced by
the global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
SELA, which co-hosted the seminar together with the China
Council for the Promotion of International Trade (CCPIT), is a
consultation and coordination group made up of 28 Latin American
and Caribbean countries.
</P>
<P>
Now the economies of the continent are opening to the rest of
the world, he said. Therefore, China and Latin America should
grasp the opportunity to further develop bilateral trade, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Trade Opportunities Between China, Latin America (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eugenio Anguiano, a former Mexican ambassador to China, said
agricultural production is very efficient in Latin America, and
thus the two sides can cooperate in this field as well as in the
textile industry.
</P>
<P>
Chinese enterprises have started making household electronic
appliances in Latin-America. They are engaged in forestry in
Brazil and build motor vehicles in Argentina, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides can cooperate in more fields with the increasing
of mutual understanding, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Compared with their respective strengths in the world economy,
China and Latin America do very little trade with each other, said
Jose Bekinschein, who is a special advisor to the Argentinian
government on the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
China's trade with Latin America was a mere 8.3 billion U.S.
dollars-worth in 1998, he said, as Latin America does most of its
business with Europe and North America. Trade with China is only
in the embryo stage, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, there are frequent visits of commercial delegations
between the two sides, a lot of economic agreements have been
signed, and bilateral investments had been increased. He said he
was confident about trade between China and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will continue tomorrow, when the Latin American
region's trade laws will be introduced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
