<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges More Attention to African Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ogata said that there are about 500,000 refugees from Sierra
Leone and Liberia and 700,000 in Great Lakes region and it calls
for more attention to their suffering.
</P>
<P>
 Answering questions about the double standard in refugee
issues, the high commissioner admitted that the suffering of
Kosovan refugees gets quick response from the international
community but some of African refugee programs are very hard to
get funds.
</P>
<P>
She argued that the emergency and seriousness of the refugee
situation also draw world attention, citing that in 1994 the
miserable condition of Rwanda refugees attracted great attentions
from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Ogata arrived in Nairobi Sunday night and left for Kigali
Monday morning. In her June 21 to 28 visit to Rwanda, Burundi and
Democratic Republic of Congo, Ogata is scheduled to talk with
governmental ministers and other high-ranking officials, urging
them to protect and aid refugees and not to forcefully deport
refugees.
</P>
<P>
She will also visit refugee camps to inspect the UNHCR staff's
work. 
</P>
