<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Cyprus Hail G-8 Decision on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Cyprus welcomed a G-8
decision made in Cologne on Monday that may -- based on U.N.
Security Council resolutions and international laws -- help solve
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks in Athens, Greek Defense Minister
Akis Tsohatzopoulos and his visiting Cypriot counterpart Yannakis
Chryssostomis described the G-8 decision on Cyprus as "positive."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. decision will invite both sides in Cyprus to hold
talks this autumn. It will also encourage the two sides to
continue their negotiations without preconditions until a
settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
While complaining that two sets of standards have been applied
in Cyprus for the past 25 years, Tsohatzopoulos said that any
agreement signed by Greece and Cyprus would require a balanced
joint defense doctrine between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus would maintain responsibility for its armaments
program, adding that the installation of the Russian-made S-300
anti-aircraft missiles on the southern Greek island of Crete would
be completed within the next three months.
</P>
<P>
Chryssostomis, who arrived here on Monday for a visit, thanked
Greece for its support in seeking methods to peacefully solve
problems on the island. The island has been divided since 1974
when Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of
Cyprus in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two ministers also discussed future
bilateral cooperation in the military field, primarily in
conducting joint training exercises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. Declare "Partnership for a New Century" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and the
United States are going to assume "world-wide responsibility" and
form a "Partnership for a new century," said their joint statement
issued here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The EU-US summit in Bonn, attended by U.S. President Bill
Clinton, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, and acting European
Commission President Jacques Santer, was focused on funding the
Balkan reconstruction, and defusing the US-EU trade conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The EU and the United States will follow the Kosovo model of co-
operation, while coping with challenges such as cross-border
threats and regional instability, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The two also agreed on the principle and mechanism of an "early
warning system" to prevent possible regional arguments and
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The statement acknowledged the role of the United Nations in
preventing and managing the international crises. "We fully
recognize the uppermost responsibility of the U.N. Security
Council in maintaining international peace and security," it read.
</P>
<P>
The US and EU, said NATO, remain the central element of the so-
called "trans-Atlantic security." They agreed to improve Europe's
capability of crisis management and to strengthen the "European
pillar of the NATO," namely the West European Union (WEU).
</P>
<P>
The WEU, a bloc including 10 European NATO members, is due to
merge with the EU in the year 2002 to make up the military section
of the EU.
</P>
<P>
On global trade issues, the statement said the World Trade
Organization (WTO) should become more open, more transparent, and
more accessible. It will be the theme for the new world trade
round scheduled for the year 2000, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
