<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Voices Concerns for Canada's "Internet Kids" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- With a booming generation of "
Internet kids" emerging in Canada, voices are being raised
challenging the validity of the educational system to provide "
reading and writing fundamentals."
</P>
<P>
A majority of Canadians say that too much emphasis is being
placed on computers in the classroom, a report by the "Globe and
Mail" newspaper said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a national education poll conducted in May, the report
said that 56 percent of 1,115 Canadians in the survey felt
students were spending too much class time on computers.
</P>
<P>
The poll uncovered serious reservations about the reading and
writing abilities of today's high-school graduates, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Only 34 percent of those surveyed held the view that "today's
high school graduates have solid reading and writing skills,"
while 65 percent disagreed.
</P>
<P>
"Computers are not going to go away. However, I think the data
tells us that finding the right balance, making sure students are
well-grounded in the fundamentals, is important," said John Write,
Vice-president of the Angus Reid Group which launched the poll.
</P>
<P>
One-third of Canadian households have been hooked up with the
Internet since it entered the life of Canadians 10 years ago,
according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
