<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Men Flee for Fear of Ethiopian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 21 (Xinhua)-- The pressure and the foreign
involvement in Somalia's internal affairs are increasing by the
day as the Ethiopian- Eritrean war continues along their borders.
</P>
<P>
Threats of more Ethiopian advances towards the regional capital
of Lower Shabelle, the port town of Merca, 100 kilometers south
of Mogadishu and the town of Qoryoley, are being envisaged as mass
exodus of refugees had already begun in several towns in the
region.
</P>
<P>
According to some of the refugees reaching here in Mogadishu,
the fear has especially increased after the Ethiopia-backed
Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA) fighters have captured Baidoa
town, an important point in southern Somalia, early in the month
and enlarged their sphere of control to Bur Hakaba Town
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
The fleeing people reaching here in Mogadishu who are mainly
the supporters of faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid, said they
have arrived from Qoryoleh, about 65 kms Southwest of the
capital, where the Oromo ethnic Ethiopians were allegedly given
the military base after they descended from a mysterious ship
that docked in the port town of Merca on May 4 this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the district commissioner of Qoryoley Town, Ali
Hussein Aliyow Ibrow, has denied that the people of the town are
fleeing their houses in fear of a possible Ethiopian incursion.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Ibrow said there are some individuals who left the
town on what he called their own wills.
</P>
<P>
In another development, 21 local organizations called The
peace &AMP; Human Rights Network, issued a communique Monday after
holding an unusual emergency session in south Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
In their communique, the peace network has expressed concern
over the mass infusion of weapons and illegal bank notes into
Somalia which they said are further aggravating the already
volatile situation of the horn of African country.
</P>
<P>
The communique has condemned both Ethiopia and Eritrea for
their direct involvement into Somalia's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The peace Network has also asked the Somali faction leaders not
to assist those countries in their endeavor of making Somalia a
battlefield for their differences.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian and Canadian companies that assisted some Somalis in
printing the illegal bank notes are also condemned for causing a
horrible inflation devastating the poor economy of Somalia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
