<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's GDP Decline Continues to Narrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The year-on-year rate of decline
in Hong Kong's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) continued to narrow,
to 3.4 percent in real terms in the first quarter of 1999,
according to preliminary estimates released by the Census and
Statistics Department here Monday.
</P>
<P>
This compared with the 6.8 percent in the third quarter and 5.7
percent in the fourth quarter of 1998, the Department says.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary GDP estimate for the first quarter of 1999
matches closely with the crude initial assessment of around 3.5
percent decline released in the "First Quarter Economic Report
1999" published on May 28,1999.
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by major GDP components on a year-on-year basis,
private consumption expenditure fell by 4.8 percent in real terms
in the first quarter of 1999. This likewise represented a relative
improvement from the decline of 9.1 percent in the fourth quarter
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Government consumption expenditure in national account terms
grew by 4.4 percent in real terms in the first quarter of 1999,
compared with a 2.5 percent increase in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
On visible trade, total exports of goods fell by 4.8 percent in
real terms in the first quarter of 1999, considerably smaller than
the 9.6 percent decrease in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Imports of goods fell by 10.3 percent in real terms in the
first quarter of 1999, also smaller than the 13.5 percent decline
in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
On invisible trade, exports of services resumed a positive
growth of 1.4 percent in real terms in the first quarter of 1999,
compared with a 0.2 percent decline in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports of services recorded a marginal decrease of
0.2 percent in real terms in the first quarter of 1999, having
fallen by 2.0 percent in the preceding quarter.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman noted that the rate of
decline in GDP, in terms of both the year-on-year and seasonally
adjusted quarter to quarter comparisons, had moderated
considerably in the first quarter of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
