<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate to Resume Debate on Nominees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's senate has received the
curricula vitaes of some minister nominees and is expected to
resume its debate on the cabinet nominees Tuesday, said This Day,
a major Nigerian daily Monday.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of the vitaes and other relevant information as
are required by the senate will enable the committee of the whole
house to raise questions on the antecedents, experience and
characters of the nominees.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources close to the Senate as saying that
 President Olusegun Obasanjo was "determined to ensure that none
of the nominees is rejected at the end of the Senate screening."
</P>
<P>
The 109-member senate asked the president to provide them with
more information barely hours after it kicking off the screening
process on June 16.
</P>
<P>
Only five candidates so far on the nomination list have been
accepted by the senate while others are pending on further
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
But the delayed screening process is already under severe
criticism, as some senators have been accused of accepting bribe
offers, said This Day.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, Senator Gbenga Aluko described lately
in Abuja that the situation necessitate his pushing for a motion
Tuesday asking the senate to disqualify any nominee found to have
offered monetary or material inducements to senators.
</P>
<P>
"It will be easy to point out ulterior reasons when a nominee
offers money to be cleared. The implications of such an act could
be that such a nominee does not really want to serve, but has the
intention of using his position to line his pocket." said Senator
Aluko. 
</P>
</TEXT>
