<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Singapore to Resume Naval Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Malaysian Navy
(RMN) and the Republic of Singapore Navy are expected to resume
their joint exercise code-named Malapura, RMN Chief Vice Admiral
Abu Bakar Abdul Jamal said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Abu Bakar said the exercise, supposed to be held annually, has
not been held since 1997 due to the regional economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Malapura, first held in 1984, was aimed at developing better
understanding and working relationship between the two navies
through the practice of common procedures and naval techniques.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully we can continue with the exercise now that we have
come out of the economic downturn," Abu Bakar told reporters after
receiving his Singapore counterpart, Rear Admiral Richard Lim
Cherng Yih at the Ministry of Defense here.
</P>
<P>
Lim, who is due to retire at the end of this month, arrived
here Monday for a two-day visit. He also called on Armed Forces
Chief General Tan Sri Mohd Zahidi Zainuddin and Defense Minister
Abang Abu Bakar Mustapha.
</P>
<P>
Abu Bakar said the two navies have enjoyed good relations.
</P>
<P>
On multilateral cooperation, Abu Bakar said both countries
would take part in the Stardex exercise to be held in September
under the auspices of the Five-Power Defense Arrangement which
also involves Australia, Britain and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Abu Bakar also said he expects the RMN to receive its two
frigates currently undergoing trials in Britain before the
Langkawi International Maritime and Aerospace Exhibition to be
held from November 30 to December 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
