<HEADLINE> HK Police Investigates Olympic Football Match Disturbance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong police are
investigating a pitch invasion incident between Nepalese fans and
Malaysian players on Sunday, according to a government press
release here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The match was one of the Asian Group Six matches for the 2000
Olympic Qualification tournament.
</P>
<P>
One coach and three players of the Malaysian team were injured
in the incident and were treated and discharged from hospital.
</P>
<P>
The match, which was stopped two minutes before the final
whistle, was at one-all before the brawl happened.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said police began reinforcing at the stadium
when the excitable mood of some of the Nepalese football fans was
first spotted by the police commander around eight minutes before
the pitch invasion.
</P>
<P>
"This did not succeed in preventing the pitch invasion when the
Nepal team scored due to the size of the invaders, around 200, and
the design of the stadium which allows easy access to the pitch
from the stand as a safety feature," said district commander Tsang
Wai-hung.
</P>
<P>
The assault incident lasted for around three minutes before
order was restored by police deployed at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the case has been classified as assault
occasioning actual bodily harm. No arrest has been made so far and
investigations are continuing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
