<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tai'an to Restore Historical Sites to Original Appearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- In order to recapture the original
beauty of the centuries-old Dai Temple, the Tai'an municipal
government will remove several of its departments which at present
occupy a quarter of the temple site, located in the old city area
of Tai'an, one of the country's leading tourism destinations in
east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The Dai Temple, which was initially built in the Qin Dynasty (B.
C. 221-207) and then expanded in the Song Dynasty (960-1279), now
covers 96,500 sq m and is regarded as the largest ancient-
architecture garden preserved in Tai'an.
</P>
<P>
The temple, which is located at the foot of Mount Taishan, will
be one of a number of historical sites and scenic spots in the
city protected from the pollution and encroachment of modern urban
life.
</P>
<P>
This is because the local government is stepping up a sweeping
program to move all local government departments, administrative
organizations and part of the enterprises, as well as nearly one-
third of its citizens out of the old city area into newly-built
areas, to the west of the old quarter.
</P>
<P>
The new city areas will cover nearly 40 sq km, about two-thirds
of the old city areas. Construction work in the new areas is going
on smoothly, and the first new residential quarter has already
taken shape and is ready for use.
</P>
<P>
At a cost of 1.5 billion yuan, the local relocation program
began in February this year and is scheduled to last 3 to 5 years.
</P>
<P>
Tai'an, which is 67 km from this capital of Shandong Province,
has been boosting its local economy by making full use of its rich
tourism resources. It earned 2 billion yuan-worth of income from
tourism in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mount Taishan alone attracts an average of 30,000 domestic and
overseas visitors every day. They come to view more than 20
ancient examples of architecture and hundreds of ancient stone
inscriptions located on the mountain, which was added to the World
Heritage list of culture and nature sites by UNESCO in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Close to the mountain are scattered a number of relic sites,
including the spot where the first human fossilized teeth were
found dating back 50,000 years. All these add to the attractions
of Tai'an, which generated 34.4 billion yuan in GDP in 1998.
</P>
<P>
A booming economy, together with the fast-growing number of
citizens in local urban areas have gradually cast shadows over the
old scenic city, as a result of skyscraper buildings, exhaust
emissions from automobiles, pollution, noise and dust.
</P>
<P>
However, with the growing of more greenery, the transformed old
city will become the cultural and tourism center of Tai'an, and is
expected to increase its income from tourism by 30 percent
annually during the first few years after the completion of the
relocation projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Denies Fighting over Weekend With Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROIBI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea Monday denied any
fighting occurred on its border with Ethiopia over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean Foreign Ministry released the news following the
reports from Addis Ababa that Ethiopia had repelled new Eritrean
offensive over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The release reaching here Monday said that "there had been no
fighting since early last week when the Ethiopia ceased its
offensives after successive defeats."
</P>
<P>
"The accounts coming from Addis Ababa are, in keeping with
pattern, completely without basis and designed to mislead the
Ethiopian people," said Tesfamariam Tekeste, head of Asia and
Australia Desk at the foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea also denied Sunday a report from the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) that it had occupied territory of neighboring
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
In recent heavy border fighting, Ethiopia claimed that its army
had put 24,450 Eritrean troops out of action.
</P>
<P>
While Eritrea said its forces had downed four Mig-23 fighter
planes and one helicopter gun ship in the Ethiopian fleet, and
killed and wounded 18, 000 Ethiopian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The two Horn of African neighbors began their border conflicts
in May 1998. Although both sides agreed to the OAU peace
framework, there is still no sight for immediate resolution to the
one-year-long conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
