<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karachi Stock Index Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Karachi Stock Exchange (KSE)
index closed higher Monday amid thin volume due to the uncertain
situation in Kashmir, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The KSE-100 index rose 13.96 points, or 1.32 percent, to
1,066.15 against 1,052.19 last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of trade on Monday stood at 64.387 million
shares against last Friday's 143.381 million shares.
</P>
<P>
"The market lacked direction and the uncertain political
situation in Kashmir is shying away the genuine investors who are
preferring to stay at sidelines," said Shakeel Anwar Kamal, a
dealer with Prudential Securities Pvt. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
He said the Group of Eight countries have also stressed the
need for holding talks on the Kashmir dispute as unless the
fundamentals are cleared, the genuine investors are not keen on
entering the market.
</P>
<P>
"There was little buying in blue chip stocks as the market
players found the present rates to be at attractive levels which
could help in booking profits if the situation (in Kashmir)
improves," said Imran Afzal, a dealer with Yusuf Ibrahim Brokerage
house.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to dip in the coming session as long as
the situation in Kashmir remains tense and there is a war-like
situation, Afzal said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
