<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inland China, Hong Kong Reach Accord on Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The authorities of inland China
and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) have
reached an agreement on the implementation of mutual arbitration.
</P>
<P>
A document to this effect was signed here today by Shen Deyong,
Vice-president of the Supreme People's Court, and Elsie Leung Oi-
Sie, Secretary of Justice of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The document was the result of talks held in accordance with
the Basic Law on Hong Kong and bringing into due consideration the
realities of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, arbitration made by one side's
courts is binding on the other side. It says if a privy on one
side does not perform the arbitration, the other party has the
right to ask the court of the reluctant privy's residence or where
the privy's property is located to implement the arbitration.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed that China's supreme court will
publish explanations on the document, while the HKSAR government
is to revise Hong Kong's existing regulations on arbitration, and
make them public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
