<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book on Japan's Invasion Tactics Found in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A book in the original Japanese
outlining the preparations for Japan's invasion of China in the
1930s has recently been discovered in Harbin, northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
It has been preserved by a Chinese folk collector and was
written by a Japanese military officer named Heijio Uchida at the
Harbin garrison. Printed in April 1934, the yellow-stained book,
which is 19 cm by 13 cm, includes 23 military photographs and
maps in its 317 pages.
</P>
<P>
Da Zhigang, Assistant Professor in the Research Center of
Japanese Affairs of the Heilongjiang Social Sciences Academy, said
that the discovery is of great importance in the study of Japanese
intentions before its invasion of China in 1936, the Second World
War, and the modern military history.
</P>
<P>
The book also contains a Japanese analysis of the international
situation in 1936, the Far East Area in particular; comparing
military forces, strategic deployment, and the military
relationship between the previous Soviet Union, the United States
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
A detailed document of Japan's military and political policies
at that time, and the invasion of China and the Pacific War
thereafter, it confirmed that the book was obviously a reference
for Japan's military leaders.
</P>
<P>
Da said that there is considerable and specific data,
especially pictures which show explicitly that the Japanese had
made much preparation before taking action. This strongly refutes
the explanations and claims by a small group of Japanese right
wing people that " Japan was forced to declare war at that time."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
