<HEADLINE> Papua New Guinea to Buy Thai Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Thai rice may find its way to
Papua New Guinea (PNG), as the Pacific island state has expressed
interest in buying Thai rice, a senior official from the Thai
Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperatives Ministry said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director-General of the Department of Agriculture Anant Dalodom
said negotiations in this regard between the two governments have
been progressed.
</P>
<P>
Ministers in charge of agricultural products in Papua New
Guinea had visited Thailand three times to discuss with their Thai
counterparts the possibility of purchasing Thai rice, Anant said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Papua New Guinea agreed to buy Thai rice provided
that the Thai Agriculture Ministry issues a certificate verifying
that the purchased rice is of high quality and disease and
insect-free.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 90 percent of the rice imported into Papua New
Guinea are from Australia, which convinced its neighbor that its
rice is of higher quality than that of others.
</P>
<P>
"Authorities from Papua New Guinea have learned by themselves
that Thai rice is of the highest quality, and has been very
popular in the international market," Anant said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the ministry is willing to issue the
certificate as required.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is the world's largest rice exporter, sharing 30
percent of the world market. The country exported 6.5 million tons
of rice in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
