<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historical Sites To Recapture Original Appearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- In order to recapture the original
beauty of a centuries-old Dai Temple, the Tai'an municipal
government departments, which occupy a quarter of its surrounding
area will be relocated from within the temple site, in the old
city areas of Tai'an, one of the country's leading tourist
destinations in east Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The Dai Temple, which was initially built in the Qin Dynasty (B.
C. 221-207) and then expanded in the Song Dynasty (960-1279), now
covers 96,500 sq m and is regarded as the largest ancient-
architecture garden preserved in Tai'an.
</P>
<P>
The temple will be one of the historical sites and scenic spots
in the city, which is at the southern foot of the Taishan Mountain,
enabling it to recapture its original appearance.
</P>
<P>
This is because the local government is stepping up a sweeping
program to move all local government departments, administrative
organizations and enterprises, as well as nearly one-third of its
citizens out of the old city area into newly-built areas, to the
west of the old region.
</P>
<P>
The new city areas will cover nearly 40 sq km, about two-thirds
of the old city areas. Construction work in the new areas is going
on smoothly and the first new residential quarter has already
taken shape and is ready for use.
</P>
<P>
At a cost of 1.5 billion yuan, the local relocation program
began in February this year and is scheduled to last 3 to 5 years
and as many as 200,000 residents will be rehoused.
</P>
<P>
Tai'an, which is 67 km away from the capital of Jinan in
Shandong Province, has been boosting its local economy by making
full use of its rich tourism resources. It earned 2 billion yuan
worth of income from tourism in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the Taishan mountain alone, every day there are an
average of 30,000 domestic and overseas people who visit more than
20 ancient architectures and hundreds of ancient stone
inscriptions in the mountain, which was added to the World
Heritage list of culture and nature sites by UNESCO in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Close to the Taishan mountain are scattered a number of relic
sites, including the spot where the first human fossilized teeth
were found dating back 50,000 years. All these add to the
attractions of Tai'an, which generated 34.4 billion yuan in GDP in
1998.
</P>
<P>
A booming economic development together with the fast-growing
number of citizens in local urban areas have gradually cast
shadows over the old scenic city, as a result of skyscraper
buildings, exhaust emissions from automobiles, pollution, noise
and dust.
</P>
<P>
However, with the growing of more greenery, the transformed old
city will become the cultural and tourism center in Tai'an and is
expected to increase its income from tourism by 30 percent
annually during the first few years after the completion of the
relocation projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects West's Concern over Jews' Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran Monday rejected the concerns
expressed by western countries on the arrest of 13 Iranian Jews on
espionage charges.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Jews were nabbed on espionage charges and the
arrest had "nothing to do with their religion and beliefs,"
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in response to concerns expressed recently
by French and Canadian foreign ministers over the arrest of
Iranian Jews. The ministers also called for their release.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said that there was no ground whatsoever for the concern
voiced by certain countries, which "are being emboldened by
certain international circles."
</P>
<P>
"All those arrested are Iranian citizens and their trial on
charges of espionage with an aim to targeting Iran's national
security is an internal issue and the indisputable right of any
country," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the arrested people were charged with
operation against Iran's national security with the aid of foreign
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Any attempt to influence the trend of their fair trial will be
tantamount to interference in the internal affairs of the Islamic
Republic of Iran and rejected by all the legal decision-making
centers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Iran confirmed the arrest of 13 Iranian
Jews on charges of spying for Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
However, both Washington and Tel Aviv denied any links between
the Iranian Jews and the Israeli and U.S. intelligence services,
urging Tehran to release the Jews.
</P>
<P>
Some Iranian judicial officials have warned that the Iranian
Jews might face death sentences according to the Iranian law.
</P>
</TEXT>
