<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obasanjo's Nomination Criticized for Biased to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some 42 members of the House of Representatives, mainly from
the northern part of the west African country, alleged on Thursday
that Obasanjo's actions since assuming his office on May 29
suggest plans to marginalize the north.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper The Punch Monday quoted presidency sources as
saying Sunday that Obasanjo and his team are unhappy and
uncomfortable with the criticisms and allegations.
</P>
<P>
Doyin Okupe, presidential adviser on media and publicity,
Friday expressed concern over the allegation of bias, describing
it as unfair and unfounded.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "just like the vice-president said, the
appointments were based on professional competence, rather than
ethnic or religious considerations."
</P>
<P>
Looking at the list of ministerial nominees, the adviser added,
"each state has at least a representative, there are 25 from the
North and 24 from the South."
</P>
<P>
Chief Maurice Ibekwe, member of the House of Representative,
described the current developments as "sad and worrisome."
</P>
<P>
He noted that "time has come when where you come from should
not be the basis for appointment, but competence, and Mr.
President is doing just that. "
</P>
<P>
National Vice-Chairman of the Alliance for Democracy (AD) in
the southwest Chief Ayo Fasanmi told the newspaper that there was
no basis for the antagonism of the president over his actions so
far.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo's anti-corruption crusade and other actions which are
geared towards ensuring equity deserved a commendation by all
Nigerians, Fasanmi stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
