<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Report Over Talks with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran Monday denied a report by an
Israeli newspaper that Iranian President Mohammad Khatami has
proposed secret dialogs with Israel on disarmament in order to
build confidence between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi strongly
dismissed the report as "baseless," the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli daily Haaretz reported Sunday that President
Khatami has proposed dialogs with Israel on signing of arms
control treaties as a first step toward confidence-building.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that Khatami asked British officials to convey
his message to Israel to remove distrust and suspicion between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman said that the propaganda ploys of the
Israeli mass media have proven "ineffective and worthless."
</P>
<P>
Misinformation campaign by the Israeli propaganda machine is
a futile attempt to mar the image of Iran, especially with
respect to recent achievements of President Khatami's
administration in the region and at international forums, he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the Islamic revolution in 1979, Israel enjoyed good
relations with the former Iranian shah regime.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries became arch foes after the Islamic
Republic of Iran rejected recognization of Israel and accused it of
usurping of the Arab land.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, Iran deemed Israel as a major
threat to the regional security and stability while Israel
expressed concern over Iran's military development.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have run into new tensions over the recent
arrest of 13 Iranian Jews whom the Iranian authorities charged
with spying for Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
However, both Tel Aviv and Washington denied any link between
the Iranians and their intelligence services, urging Iran to
release the Iranian Jews.
</P>
<P>
Iranian authorities have rejected the concerns expressed by
western countries over the arrest, and claimed that the Iranian
Jews might be sentenced to death for spying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Deports 18,000 Zimbabweans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has deported about
18,000 Zimbabweans, who are said to have illegally settled in the
country this year, Zimbabwe's police said.
</P>
<P>
Many Zimbabweans were crossing the border illegally to South
Africa in search of jobs while other's continued their stay well
after the expiry of their permits, the daily Herald reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Inspector Newton Mutomba in an interview in Beitbridgo of
south Zimbabwe told the Herald Sunday, "we have receive 17,929
Zimbabweans deported from South Africa from January to June 16
this year."
</P>
<P>
He said the number of deported Zimbabweans from South Africa
has already surpassed that in the whole year of 1988, which
records about 14, 000. Most of the deportee were caught on their
way to Johannesburg to seek employment.
</P>
<P>
The Herald also reported that about 3,000 Zimbabweans have so
far died in South Africa this year, most of them at the hands of
criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
