<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, KLA Agree on Demilitarization Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 21 (Xinhua) -- NATO and the Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA) signed an agreement early Monday on the
demilitarization of the guerrilla group in a bid to prevent
possible ethnic clashes.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached between Mike Jackson, commander of
the peacekeeping force in Kosovo, and the KLA leader, Hashim Thaci,
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The alliance peacekeepers would begin taking over the KLA's
arms from early Monday as both sides agreed that the agreement
took effect as of signing.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the KLA must stop all military activities,
including laying mines, putting up roadblocks as well as attacking
and abducting civilians.
</P>
<P>
The KLA is asked to close all its positions, remove the
sentries set up along the roads and mark the location of mines
laid by itself within four days of the signing of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Within seven days from now on, the KLA must place all its
weapons under the supervision of the peacekeeping force, clear all
mines and withdraw all its troops from the positions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the KLA is also ordered to turn over all its weapons
to the place designated by the peacekeeping force within 30 days
and the KLA members will be banned from wearing its uniforms or
any signs belonging to the guerrilla group in three months.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia's official news agency Tanjug said that all Yugoslav
troops and police units had been withdrawn from Kosovo before
Sunday midnight. NATO had expressed satisfaction with the pull-out
conducted under the U.N. Security Council resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
