<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little Possibility of Full-Scale War Between India, Pakistan: Advani </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Caretaker Home Minister L. K.
Advani said Monday that he saw little possibility of a full-scale
war between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the chances of escalation into a full-fledged
war between India and Pakistan, Advani in an exclusive interview
with Press Trust of India (PTI) here said that "because of
multiplicity of authorities in Pakistan, we cannot say there will
be no war."
</P>
<P>
Advani evaded a question whether India would go beyond the Line
of Control (LOC) in Kashmir between India and Pakistan in the
ongoing fighting to stop logistical support to the intruders in
Kargil sector of Kashmir. The earlier local media reports said
that India had heavily shelled the Pakistan-Occupied Kashmir (POK)
areas to cut off the supply lines of the intruders.
</P>
<P>
Indian former army chief general (RETD) Shankar Roychowdhury
has said that it is an impractical proposition for the army to
flush out the intruders without crossing the LOC.
</P>
<P>
India launched a big military operation from early May to
"flush out Pakistan-backed infiltrators" from the Kargil sector
and India refused to hold talks with Pakistan before it completes
its military operation in that area.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has warned India that many
more Kargil-like situations might crop up if the overall Kashmir
issue is not settled once and for all.
</P>
<P>
Advani said that it would be a limited war as invasion had been
contained and it was a matter of time before it would be foiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
