<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Announcement of Indonesia's Election Vote Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's General Election
Commission (KPU) on Monday requested that the announcement of the
final vote count be postponed, pending the settlement of all
election violations.
</P>
<P>
"The KPU had asked for the postponement so all (election)
violations could be settled first," Chairman of the Indonesian
Election Committee (PPI) Jakob Tobing said following a meeting
among members of the PPI and election monitoring committees and
leaders of political parties.
</P>
<P>
According to schedule, the PPI would announce the final vote
count at national level on Monday (June 21).
</P>
<P>
Tobing said the KPU will meet on Tuesday to decide when the
final vote count will begin.
</P>
<P>
Besides the election violations conducted by some parties in
several areas, the vote count in some provinces, such as Aceh has
not completed, Tobing said.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, the PPI has been ready to begin the final vote count
gradually because not all provincial election committees have
completed their tallies," he added.
</P>
<P>
KPU Chairman Rudini meanwhile said the final vote count could
only begin after all tabulations and other substantial data
reprocessed.
</P>
<P>
KPU is estimated to conclude its final vote count before July
8.
</P>
<P>
According to official Antara News Agency, about 78.29 percent
out of the 117,815,053 registered voters have been counted as of
01:00 p.m. local time on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The provisional results reported by Antara showed the
Indonesian Democratic party of Struggle (PDI-P) was still
front-runner, accounting for 34.13 percent of the total votes
counted, followed by ruling Golkar with 22.12 percent), the
National Awakening Party (PKB) 13.47 percent), the United
Development Party (PPP) 10.31 percent) and the National Mandate
Party (PAN) 6.97 percent.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the June 7 election
to compete for 462 out of the 500 seats in the House of
Representatives (DPR). The remaining 38 seats are reserved for the
military, whose members do not vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
