<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Cut Enlivens Chinese B-share Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua)-- China's B-share market is set for
long term prosperity following signs of the ending of the Asian
financial crisis and China's latest aggressive efforts to boost
the market.
</P>
<P>
China's fiscal authorities announced on May 29 they would
reduce the stamp tax rate from 0.4 percent to 0.3 percent. On June
2, the China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC) announced it
released control over the type of companies issuing B shares and
lifted restrictions on the number of companies issuing B shares
every year.
</P>
<P>
B shares are denominated in Renminbi and are traded on domestic
stock exchanges exclusively by foreign investors. A shares are
designed for Chinese nationals. Since 1991, 105 companies have
issued B shares on the Shenzhen and Shanghai stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
On June 9, the central bank announced further interest rate
cuts, which sent the market indexes on an upward spiral.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Mingli, a researcher from the Citic Securities Company,
said that the government's latest moves will increase the size of
the B-share market, by allowing private companies and foreign-
invested companies to issue B shares.
</P>
<P>
She added that the meager size of the market has failed to
attract enough foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
An official from the CSRC said that the commission is preparing
new measures to activate the B-share market, which will include
setting up of Sino-foreign investment funds, broadening the scope
of investors and improving the ways of issuing B shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
