<HEADLINE> 8 Policemen Wounded in Kurdish Attack in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Eight policemen were wounded, two
seriously, late Sunday night when Kurdish rebels attacked an
apartment building in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Members of the outlawed Kurdish Workers (PKK) launched the
attack in Kiziltepe town of Mardin province and fled the scene
after operation, Turkish private ATV reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The injured were rushed to Mardin Devlet Hospital for
treatment, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a statement issued by the office of the Emergency
Regional Rule said on Monday that the Turkish security forces had
killed seven PKK rebels in recent military operations in
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Four PKK guerrillas surrendered to the security forces in the
region, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 15-year-old war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey since 1984. Conflicts between
the government troops and the PKK have ever since claimed over
37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
