<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defending Champions Norway Defeat Russia 2-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Norway
started their World Cup road with a 2-1 victory over Russia in a
group c match at Boston.
</P>
<P>
The defending champions, hoping to win their second World Cup
title, were held by new-comers Russia for much of the match.
</P>
<P>
Yet Marianne Pettersen and Brit Sandaune were still too much for
the Russian defense line. They each had a goal and an assist to
give Norway the victory.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegians dominated the match from the very beginning. They
nearly opened the scoring at the first minute, but their first goal
didn't come until the 28th minute as Sandaune sent home a cross from
Pettersen.
</P>
<P>
Norway had lots of scoring chances after that but their second
goal came as late as at the 68th minute. Pettersen collected a
rebound and just shot past the Russian goal-keeper.
</P>
<P>
After the two goals, the Russian team tried to push forward and
their efforts were rewarded as Galina Komarova blasted home at the
78th minute.
</P>
<P>
The Russian coach Yurii Bystritzkii was quite satisfied with the
match:"We're already relatively happy since we can take part in the
World Cup. Now we're looking at our next two games and hope to get
into the second round."
</P>
<P>
The win put Norway on top of group c with three points. Japan
and Canada played to a 1-1 tie at San Jose on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Police Introduces Code of Conduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean National Police
Agency on Monday announced a 12-point code of conduct for police
staff in a bid to eradicate corruption and establish discipline.
</P>
<P>
Under the new code of ethics, policemen are banned from
operating or taking part in management of bars, pubs, adult game
rooms, and other entertainment businesses.
</P>
<P>
The code also does not allow police to gamble, to drink alcohol
while on duty, and to drive under the influence of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
South Korean police officers have often been criticized for
receiving bribes from bars, night clubs, and other entertainment
businesses in red-light zones by abusing their power and peddling
their influence.
</P>
<P>
The police agency said that it will sternly punish those who
are found in violation of the code regardless of their rank and
record.
</P>
<P>
The new code of ethics came one week after the government
introduced a 10-point code of ethics for civil servants, which
banned them from receiving presents valued at or above 50,000 won
(some 40 dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
