<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Two refineries, one for oil and the other for gas,
have been established in Abu Dhabi in the United Arab Emirates,
with 500 million dirhams (186 million U.S. dollars) of capital for
each company, it was officially announced here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Khalifa Bin Zayed Al Nahyan, crown prince of Abu Dhabi
and chairman of the Higher Petroleum Board, issued the relative
regulations for the Abu Dhabi Company for Oil Refining and the
Abu Dhabi Gas Company.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Kuwaiti Development Fund will provide Egypt with
26.35 million Kuwaiti dinars (87 million dollars) in soft loans
for a reclamation project of 400,000 feddans (168,000 hectares) in
north Sinai.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to this effect was signed Sunday with Egyptian
government. The Kuwaiti fund has signed 21 loan agreements with
Egypt, with the capital totaling 251 million dinars (815.8 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The U.S. Microsoft, the world's largest software
company, has officially opened its regional office here after
Lebanon's new intellectual property rights law went into effect on
June 15, the Arabic-language Al Anwar reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The new office, which is responsible for Microsoft's business
in Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and Cyprus, opened last Friday, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly believe that Lebanon has the basic principles to be
the IT center for the Middle East," Nasser Saidi, Lebanese
minister of trade and economy, said at the office's inaugural
dinner.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's consumer price index for May showed that
wholesale poultry prices dropped by 17 percent, the Daily Star
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The drop was not fully reflected in retail prices, which fell
by 3.81 percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
One of the noticeable decreases was in egg prices, which fell
by 8.74 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prices on dairy products, mainly cheese, also fell.
</P>
<P>
However, cheese price is expected to rise with the
implementation of the new Customs duties in June, which average 6
percent on cheese imports, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Italy here Sunday started a two-day seminar
on management of drinking water and sewage treatment networks.
</P>
<P>
The seminar is studying ways to implement joint projects
concerning drinking water and sewage treatment in Iran or in a
third country, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Energy Minister for Urban Water and Sewage
Treatment Affairs Gholamreza Manuchehri said at the seminar that
Iran's ability in the water and sewage treatment sector and the
Italian capability in carrying out projects in this sector have
prepared ground for their cooperation in third countries.
</P>
<P>
Italian ambassador to Iran Ludovico Ortona told the seminar
that Italy was Iran's biggest trade partner in 1997 and 1998, with
the volume at 2.3 billion dollars in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
