<HEADLINE> China Produces Cloned Embryo of Giant Panda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists announced today
that they have successfully developed an embryo of a giant panda
using clone technology, which could be a critical and exciting
breakthrough for saving an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Chinese Academy of Sciences explained that
they had introduced the cells of a dead female panda into the egg
cells of a Japanese white rabbit. They then spent 10 months
carefully nurturing the embryo, which was a year ahead of
expectations.
</P>
<P>
Chen Dayuan, a scientist from the academy's Animal Research
Institute, said that they are now trying to place the embryo in
the womb of a selected host animal which hopefully won't reject it.
If it works, they will possibly have created the world's first
cloned panda.
</P>
<P>
China recently announced plans to try and clone the giant panda
within three to five years, but Chen said that the scientists now
believe they can reach the goal in a shorter time.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is unique to China and only around 1,000 now
live in the wild and 100 in zoos. Experts have warned that
extinction of the animal is imminent in a couple of dozen of years.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda has lived on the planet for eight million years
but it is the low reproduction rate that has led to drastic
reduction in the species. Artificial reproduction methods have
been tried in recent years but are not very effective.
</P>
<P>
The body cells the Chinese scientists used were from the bone
muscle, womb epidermis and mammary gland. Experiments showed that
the mammary cells achieved the best anastomosis with the egg cells
of the rabbit.
</P>
<P>
DNA analysis showed that the genetic characteristics of the
embryo are the same as that of the panda's somatic cell,
indicating that the cloned animal is without doubt a panda rather
than a rabbit.
</P>
<P>
American scientists have recently used the same method, known
as inter-species clone technology, to produce an embryo of the
rare argali. But an unfortunate abortion resulted in an unpleasant
ending of the experiment.
</P>
<P>
However, both the American and Chinese examples demonstrate
that the cloning of animals that are at the edge of extinction is
feasible, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, a British scientist successfully bred the world's
first cloned animal Dolly the sheep. The technique he used is
called intra-species cloning, with which the body cells and egg
cells are taken from the same animal species.
</P>
<P>
However, cells used in inter-species cloning are taken out from
different sorts of animals, and tend to be more difficult to
handle.
</P>
<P>
Biologists believe that intra-species cloning is not practical
in reproducing rare animals because their number is too small to
obtain eggs. Therefore, the research into inter-species cloning
should be stepped up.
</P>
<P>
The cloning of the giant panda was first proposed by Chen in
March 1997, and was then set as a leading program by the Chinese
Academy of Sciences and the Ministry of Science and Technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
