<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Oilfield in Western Part of South China Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The largest oilfield in the
western part of the South China began operation 110 days ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
Information from the South China Sea (West) Oil Corporation,
which runs the oilfield, said that the new oilfield, Wei 12-1
oilfield, situated 30 km to the southwest of Weizhou Islet in the
Beibu Gulf, started operation on June 12.
</P>
<P>
It is capable of producing one million tons of crude annually
and 500,000 cu m of natural gas daily. The new oilfield is in the
middle of two other existing oilfields in the same gulf and is
connected to the two by a 30-km-long seabed pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The oil and gas produced by the three oilfields is transferred
to a plant on the Weizhou Islet. The plant is capable of
processing two million tons of petroleum annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
