<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bird Preserve Built in North Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China has built a preserve for
birds on marshy land amidst large tracts of desert in the Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region recently.
</P>
<P>
The Shahu Preserve is 56 k.m. from Yinchuan, the region's
capital, on an 895-hectare lake and 1,800-hectare swamp area
amidst 1,500 hetares of sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
The preserve has 63 plants and 144 vertebrates, including 16
types of fish and 98 types of birds, some of which are under state
protection.
</P>
<P>
About 120,000 birds are born annually in the marsh, which is a
"paradise for birds", according to Bai Xinlian, director of the
preserve's office.  
</P>
</TEXT>
