<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Porcelain Kilns Unearthed in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Archeological workers have unearthed
about 100 Yaozhou porcelain kilns covering more than 15,000 square
meters in northwest China's Shaanxi Province over the past 15
years.
</P>
<P>
Yaozhou porcelain is renowned as one of the sixth most famous
ceramics from ancient China and it can be traced back to the early
Tang dynasty (618 A.D. - 907). The kilns are located in the
ancient city of Yaozhou, at a site of more than 80 kilometers
north of Xi'an, Shaanxi's provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
The discoveries include actual kilns and more than one million
articles and tens of thousands of relevant items of equipment. And
tens of thousands of the articles can be restored, a local source
said.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest area of ancient porcelain kilns that has
been unearthed in China, and it will help research into the
history of ancient Chinese ceramics, archeologists noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
