<HEADLINE> Silkworm Breeding Promotes Growth in North China's Ningxia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The silkworm-breeding business is
playing a more important role in the economic growth of North
China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The region has 20,000 mu (1,300 hectares) planted in mulberry
trees, 7,000 mu (470 hectares) of which was just added this year.
Seven years ago, only a few farmers in Ningxia raised silkworms, a
local source says.
</P>
<P>
Last year's silkworm cocoon output reached 230 tons, bringing 4.
6 million yuan to local farmers. The Ningxia silk has a better
quality than that of other parts of the country and costs 10 to 20
percent more on market, officials say.
</P>
<P>
The region has set up a large distribution center and a dozen
technological service centers for silkworm raisers. The Ministry
of Science and Technology and the China Silk Import and Export
Corporation have showed interest in turning the region into a
state-level high-quality silk center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
