<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Refuses Law-Breaking Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will forcibly
repatriate refugees found guilty of breaking local and
international laws, Minister for Home Affairs Ali Ameir Mohamed
has said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to mark the African Refugee Day Sunday, Ameir
said serious violations of domestic and international laws by
refugees would not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania will continue sheltering refugees from Burundi and
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)," he said, "but such
generosity should not be regarded by refugees as permission to
break laws."
</P>
<P>
Ameir called on refugees to observe existing laws in Tanzania
and international conventions governing their stay in a host
country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 74,821 refugees from both
Burundi and the DRC have entered the western Kigoma Region over
the past 10 months, increasing the total number of refugees in
Tanzania to over 300,000.
</P>
<P>
The refugees have been fleeing fierce military battles in the
neighboring states in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
As the 30th anniversary of Africa Refugee Day was celebrated
across the continent Sunday, statistics released by the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said at present
there are 6.5 million refugees in Africa out of an estimated 21.1
million worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
