<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Asks U.S. Bank to Give PAl More Time to Recover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has asked
the United States Export-Import Bank (Eximbank) to give Philippine
Airlines (PAL) more time to carry out its rehabilitation program
before taking the legal route against the debt-ridden company.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora issued this response Monday
to reports that the U.S. Eximbank has asked the U.S. Bankruptcy
Court to allow it to repossess PAL's loan-tied aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said in a news release that the Philippine government
have already written to the U.S. Eximbank, asking them to give a
little more consideration to the rehabilitation efforts of PAl.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is now up to PAl to oppose the reported move by
the U.S. Eximbank before the courts because the Philippine
government is no longer the proper party to act on this.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the U.S. Eximbank asked the U.S.
Bankruptcy Court of Northern California on June 17 to lift a
restraining order barring legal action against PAl.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said this order covers the seizure of PAL
planes or property "anywhere in the U.S.".
</P>
<P>
Zamora said that if the U.S. court allows U.S. Eximbank to
repossess the planes, it would put a "very large crimp" on PAl's
rehabilitation process.
</P>
<P>
As prescribed by U.S. bankruptcy rules, a hearing on the
Eximbank motion is expected to be called at least 28 days after
PAL has been notified.
</P>
<P>
However, PAl officials said the flag carrier management has not
been formally notified of the new case.
</P>
<P>
PAL is now undergoing a rehabilitation program after its
chairman Lucio Tan infused 200 million U.S. dollars in fresh
capital into the airline on the June 4 deadline set by the
Securities and Exchange Commission, which is supervising PAL's
rehabilitation process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
