<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ho Chi Minh City's Export Value Up More than 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Ho Chi Minh City's total export
earnings in the first six months of this year are expected to
reach 2.05 billion u.s. dollars, an increase of 10.2 percent
compared to the same period of the last year, Vietnam's English
business newspaper The Saigon Times Daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Ho Chi Minh City Statistics
Bureau, Local companies will account for 1.63 billion U.S.
dollars, a 5.8 percent increase, and the foreign-invested sector
413 million U.S. dollars, up 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Industrial goods will remain the largest export income earner,
79.7 percent of the total, and up to 16.9 percent year-on-year.
Respective figures for seafood should be 5.9 percent and 2.9
percent, and for forestry products, 1.4 percent and 24 percent.
Agrofood, with a minus growth of 33.3 percent, will account for 13
percent of the total export value.
</P>
<P>
The City's import spending is expected to reach 1.73 billion
U.S. dollars, similar to that of the first half last year. The
domestic sector is projected to spend 1.24 billion U.S. dollars, a
drop of 7.7 percent, while the foreign-invested sector should
spend 494.7 million U.S. dollars, up 25.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
