<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Shrinking Steel Output to Boost Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China's bulk steel industry is
planning an unprecedented reduction in output this year to offset
mounting financial pressure from a stagnant domestic market and
stumbling exports.
</P>
<P>
The State Economic and Trade Commission ordered the industry to
curb this year's production to 104 million tons earlier this month,
which will be 10 percent down from last year's amount.
</P>
<P>
China is now, nominally and physically, the world's largest
steel producer, since the output touched 101 million tons in 1996.
The annual production capacity has now reached 190 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Boasting a strong steel industry has been the country's long
cherished goal, since it is highlighted as a measure of national
industrial competitiveness. The industry was on a fast-track of
development as it entered 1990s.
</P>
<P>
However, an inflated production capacity, although propping up
the development of many other industries, has not brought with it
profits equal to its strength. The industry's compound profit
plunged to two billion yuan (240 million U.S. dollars) last year,
compared to its best record of 29 billion yuan (3.5 billion U.S.
dollars) in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The profit dropped at an alarming rate of 66 percent in the
first quarter of this year from the corresponding period of last
year though the output retained an upward trend of seven percent.
</P>
<P>
Some steel works have scrambled to squeeze production costs and
reduce payrolls in efforts to boost revenues. This has generated a
little benefit, although not that obvious. The industry as a whole,
however, is still suffocated by heavy debt due to redundant
production, which has led to sagging prices.
</P>
<P>
"This has resulted in a big waste of resources. The macro-
control of production has been aimed at saving the heavy losses of
the state-owned assets," said Wang Wanbin, director of the State
Administration of Metallurgical Industry (SAMI).
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the reduction could affect company
revenues for this year, it could be the only way out for the
industry in the long run, suggested Yang Xiaoning, head of China
Metallurgical Industry Development Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
He explained that state interference would propel steel
producers to wipe out outdated production lines and restructure
their product mix according to market signals.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, it is expected to drive up the market price of steel
products," Yang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Shrinking Steel Output to Boost Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A number of steel producers have made moves to brace themselves
for this reduction strategy. The Wuhan Iron and Steel (Group)
Company (WISC), one of the country's top five steel enterprises,
reported a striking 192 percent year-on-year surge in profits
under a 10-percent drop in output in the January-April period. It
earned 13.75 million U.S. dollars from steel exports in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The company has pooled more than 20 billion yuan of renovation
spending over the past few years, a considerable amount for steel
producers in China.
</P>
<P>
"Large state-owned enterprises should learn to pinch pennies.
As for now, our competitiveness is measured by technological
ability and renovations," said Liu Benren, WISC's general manager.
</P>
<P>
The company is investing heavily in a silicon-steel production
expansion project, which would increase the capacity from 70,000
tons to 400,000 tons. The high value-added product is badly needed
in the domestic market and as a result involves large amounts of
imports every year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the company's production reduction has been done by
eliminating outdated production capacity, said officials from the
company's special steel works in Huangshi City in central China's
Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
According to SAMI's forecast, this year's steel demand will be
around 100 million tons and imports will be controlled to under
seven million tons.
</P>
<P>
China has removed 30 million tons of outdated steel production
capacity over the past two years and will continue its efforts
this year. SAMI will soon send inspectors to 46 big steel
enterprises to oversee the reduction work. The production of these
companies accounts for about half of the nation's total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
