<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Forced to 1-1 Tie with Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ghana's Barikisu Tettey-Quao was sent off at the 26th minute, but
their goal-keeper Memunatu Sulemana put up a heroic performance,
allowing Ghana to come away with a point.
</P>
<P>
The match was plagued by rough tackles and at the 26th minute,
Tettey-Quao made a dangerous tackle and was sent off. The Ghana
team had to play the rest of the game with one player less.
</P>
<P>
But it was Ghana which played more aggressively after the sending
off while the Australian team appeared a little bit too relaxed.
</P>
<P>
For most time of the match, the Australian team put heavy
pressure on the Ghana defense. But their efforts were all turned
down by brilliant saves by the 21-year-old Sulemana.
</P>
<P>
Both teams failed to score in the first 70 minutes and the game
seemed to be headed for a goalless draw.
</P>
<P>
But at the 74th minute, Australia broke the deadlock through
captain Julie Murray. Ghana's defense was got caught off position
and Murray collected a loose ball and unleashed a poised shot past
Sulemana from about eight meters out.
</P>
<P>
Only one minute later, Ghana got the equalizer as Vivian
Mensah's shot was blocked by Australian goal-keeper Wheeler and
the rebound was slotted home by Nana Gyumfua at the right post.
</P>
<P>
The draw put Ghana and Australia on the second place of group d.
China is now at the top of the group with a 2-1 victory over Sweden
on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
