<HEADLINE> Three People Arrested for Faulty Highway Culverts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Police in central China's Henan
Province recently arrested three people who are suspected of being
responsible for two improperly-built culverts on a superhighway in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Local police said that Sun Jishun and Lu Chuanlin, who were
acting as the manager and deputy-manager of a real estate company
in neighboring Shaanxi Province, sold the two culverts to an
individual contractor Li Rui for 160,000 yuan (about 19,000 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Li used stone instead of concrete to build the two culverts,
which were found to have serious flaws that caused 336,000 yuan
worth of damage on the superhighway, a key state project linking
the popular tourist attraction of Luoyang with the city of
Sanmenxia.
</P>
<P>
China has increased quality inspections at engineering projects
since an improperly-built bridge collapsed in the southwestern
city of Chongqing earlier this year, killing 40.
</P>
<P>
The importance of quality on engineering projects has been
emphasized since then to help get more investment in
infrastructure to promote economic growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
