<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insects Plague Forest In Northeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- An infestation of insects in
northeast China's Liaoning Province has affected more than 200,000
hectares of forests.
</P>
<P>
A local official says that the problem is still growing and
more than 20 species of insects have been found to be involved. A
lack of diversity in tree species and the large number of small
trees have lowered the resistance to natural disasters,
specialists say.
</P>
<P>
The situation then got worse with last year's drought and the
abnormally high temperatures that helped insects survive the
winter and also caused illness in trees, according to Sun Yongping,
director of the province's forest insect disease prevention,
recently..
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has a forest coverage rate of only about 30 percent,
with 4.45 million hectares of forests.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has called for urgent help from
forestry people in felling seriously-affected trees, replacing
them with new ones, and using airplanes to spray pesticide. But
officials say that they are still uncertain whether these measures
will have much effect because such a wide area has been affected.
</P>
<P>
The insect infestation could mean a deteriorating situation and
forestry departments are keeping a close eye on the plague, Sun
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
