<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola on Brink of Humanitarian Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- In Ukama, in central Angola's
Huambo Province, some 18,000 hungry refugees are forced to turn to
rats and wild fruits for a living, as they have run out of food
supply after the rebel National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) cut off roads to the town.
</P>
<P>
Situation with the 150,000 refugees in the neighboring Kuito
City of Bie Province are not any better, with hardly enough food
for one meal a day for most of them, as the cold winter coming
nearer.
</P>
<P>
About four or five dead bodies are carried out of the refugee
camps in the city ever day.
</P>
<P>
In the comparatively calm capital city of Luanda, many have to
sleep on the streets as more and more displaced people are pouring
into the city from northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Governmental statistics show that there are about 1.6 million
refugees out of the 11 million population in the southern African
country , and almost 3.5 million to four million are directly
affected by the civil war after military conflicts between the
government and UNITA re-started by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is greatly concerned with the situation of
the refugees, which is said to be "on the brink of a humanitarian
disaster."
</P>
<P>
The UN World Food Program and other non-governmental
organizations are speeding up their aid work, with the European
Union declaring to offer 11 million Euro as emergent aid to
Angola.
</P>
<P>
But the relief work was slowed down as the UNITA military men,
who have laid land mines on major roads, are ambushing relief
workers, and the cost for the relief work is turning higher as
relief food has to be transported by air.
</P>
<P>
The Nato's bombing of Kosovo has shifted the attention of the
western world to war refugees from Yugoslavia, thus reduced the
relief donation to the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The UN World Food Program has only materialize half of their
promised aid to the refugees in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has said it is very hard for itself to
handle the deteriorating refugee situation in the country which
has been plagued by civil war for almost 28 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
