<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daya Bay Nuke Plant to Increase Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Authorities at the Daya Bay
Nuclear Power Plant in the city of Shenzhen in Guangdong Province,
south China, have been trying hard to counter the adverse effects
of the Asian financial crisis and to increase both power output
and hard currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
They say that they will employ more Chinese technicians to do
maintenance work and supervise equipment purchases to avoid
stockpiling of raw materials and wasting capital.
</P>
<P>
More Chinese equipment will be used to replace imports and to
lower power generating costs.
</P>
<P>
The plant has provided 6.22 billion kwh of electricity for the
Guangdong and Hong Kong grid so far this year, and from January to
May, it provided 3.1 billion kwh of electricity for Hong Kong,
which was a major increase from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Plant authorities say that they plan to provide 13.3 billion
kwh of electricity this year, with 9.31 billion kwh for Hong Kong
and hard currency earnings set at 550 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the plant generated 12.31 billion kwh of electricity,
provided 7.58 billion kwh to Hong Kong and earned 450 million U.S.
dollars in hard currency.
</P>
<P>
The Daya Bay plant was China's first large commercial nuclear
power plant built with foreign capital, equipment, and technology.
It is operated by the Guangdong Nuclear Investment Co. Ltd. and
Hong Kong Nuclear Investment Co. Ltd. and can generate 13.5
billion kwh of electricity annually. It began operation in 1994
with an agreement that 30 percent of the electricity would go to
Guangdong and the remainder to Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
