<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Hosts 200,000 African Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has hosted about 200,000
refugees from various war-ravaged African countries, Zambian
Deputy Minister of Home Affairs Edwin Hatembo said.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia newspaper Monday quoted Hatembo as saying that
Zambia, being a signatory to the 1951 United Nations Convention,
had assumed the obligation to look after displaced persons and
asylum seekers.
</P>
<P>
Officiated at the 30th anniversary of "Africa Refugee Day" here
 Sunday, Hatembo urged the refugees, most of whom lived in
villages without proper documentation, to settle in better areas
to access social services such as education and health.
</P>
<P>
"The policy of the government is not to encourage the
spontaneous settlement of refugees. Those who have settled in
villages are urged to move to settlements where material
assistance and social services are available," said the deputy
minister.
</P>
<P>
Hatembo said Zambia was currently host to 197,000 refugees from
Angola, Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Somalia, Rwanda and
Burundi. Among them, 15,000 were urban refugees while 47,000 had
been settled in refugee centers dotted across the country.
</P>
<P>
A further 120,000 had settled in undesignated areas, he said,
adding the government asked them to move to settlement areas.
</P>
<P>
At the same function, Oluseyi Bajulaiye, country representative
of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugee (UNHCR),
called for an end to conflicts in the southern African region
which had left thousands of people displaced.
</P>
<P>
Bajulaiye said the UNHCR was saddened by the renewed tension in
the region and commended Zambian President Frederick Chiluba for
his mediatory role to end the conflict in DRC.
</P>
<P>
The only solution to the refugee crisis was for peace and
stability to prevail in the refugees' countries of origin that
would pave way for their repatriation and re-integration, he said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
