<HEADLINE> China's Procuratorates Launch Anti-Crime Publicity Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Procuratorates across China
launched a nationwide week long publicity campaign today in a bid
to encourage the reporting of offenses and crimes.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of procurators from the country's 3,600
procuratorial organs went out on the streets to answer people's
questions related to reporting offenses and other legal issues.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Procuratorate (SPP) and Beijing's Xicheng
District Procuratorate jointly set up an information center on the
busy commercial street of Xidan. Many passers-by stopped to look
and ask for information.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qiong, deputy procurator-general of the SPP, said that
from this year China will hold a similar publicity week in the
last week of every June.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to improve the ties between the
procuratorial organs and the people, and boost the people's
enthusiasm for reporting crimes to help in the fight against the
underworld, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Procuratorial organs across China will also hold press
conferences, competitions and information forums to help spread
knowledge about legal matters.
</P>
<P>
"In the first four months of the year, procuratorates
countrywide received 128,000 reports of offenses, up 4.94 percent
over the same period of last year," Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
