<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Gyrates from Negative to Positive Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total external
trade gyrated from negative to positive territory in May 1999 with
exports growing by 2.6 percent and imports increasing by 5.9
percent, turning around from a year-long unabated declines.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said in a press release
Monday that the country's total trade expanded by 4.2 percent
year-on-year in May 1999 after 12 consecutive months of
contractions.
</P>
<P>
In May, non-oil domestic exports (NODX) grew by a hefty 7.3
percent after a marginal increase of 0.3 percent in April 1999,
non-oil re-exports (NORX) moderated its decline to 3.3 percent
from the double-digit declines in the preceding two months,
non-oil imports picked up by 4.6 percent registering the first
increase since April 1998 and oil domestic exports expanded by 5.1
percent after 20 months of continuous declines, TDB spelt out.
</P>
<P>
This is a reflection of generally improved global electronics
demand and the bottoming out of the crisis-ridden economies
including Malaysia, Thailand, South Korea and Japan, as well as
the rebounding of oil prices on global markets, TDB added.
</P>
<P>
According to TDB, domestic exports of electronic products were
up by 2.6 percent in May 1999 after eight months of consecutive
declines and domestic exports of non-electronic products expanded
strongly by 17.9 percent, reflecting the turnaround in electronic
exports and the strong expansion of non-electronic exports.
</P>
<P>
Of the top five markets, only NODX to Hong Kong continued to
shrink in May this year and NODX to the remaining top markets
recorded positive growth in the month with the U.S market growing
by 0.1 percent, the EU running up by a hefty 10.5 percent,
Malaysia increasing by 6.2 percent, Japan soaring by 24.4 percent
and Hong Kong falling by 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
NODX to Thailand, Taiwan, Australia and South Korea also grew
markedly with growth rates ranging from 8.9 percent to 64.0
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, NODX to emerging markets registered a slight
increase with positive growth seen in China and India markets and
negative growth in most of the other emerging markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
