<HEADLINE> Shanghai Doctors Help Men Who Lost Penises to Become Fathers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese doctors in Shanghai have
helped at least two men who lost their penises in accidents or
from disease to regain normal sexual activities and even become
fathers, a local hospital source revealed here today.
</P>
<P>
One was a worker from Rushan County of east China's Shandong
Province, who received a penis excision due to a malignant tumor,
and a Pakistani citizen who lost his sexual organ in a work
accident.
</P>
<P>
"Since we successfully rebuilt prosthetic penises, both
patients have got married, enjoyed a normal sex life and had
children," said a spokesman with the Shanghai No.9 People's
Hospital affiliated to the Shanghai Second Medical University.
</P>
<P>
However, the hospital declined to identify the two patients by
name.
</P>
<P>
Doctors in charge of the treatment include Dr. Cheng Kaixiang
of the Hospital's Plastic Surgery Department and Professor Huang
Wenyi with the Medical University. Zhang Disheng, an academician
with the Chinese Academy of Engineering, and several of his
colleagues were also said to have played a vital role in the
development of the hospital's penis rebuilding techniques in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
"We use skin and muscles from the patient's forearms, thighs
and stomach to rebuild the penis. This can not only increase the
diameter and length of the new organ, but also repair all sense in
nerve endings related to the patient's sexual feelings, thus
giving him a complete recovery," explained Cheng.
</P>
<P>
The new technique has been formally named after Dr. Cheng,
whose relevant thesis has been published in leading international
plastic surgery magazines, said the hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
