<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents In Northern Israel Remain in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Residents in northern Israel are
remaining in bomb shelters Monday morning after Hezbollah's
rocket attacks Sunday night in retaliation for the wounding of
three Lebanese civilians by Israeli rockets in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Israeli military officials will re-assess
the situation in the area later Monday to decide whether the
residents can leave the shelters after nervously spending a night
in underground refuges.
</P>
<P>
The residents were instructed to stay in the shelters since
Sunday afternoon after Lebanese reports said two Lebanese women
and a young girl at a village outside the Israeli-occupied
security zone were wounded by a missile fired by the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
In the night, the Hezbollah, or Party of God, fired two
Katyusha rockets Sunday night at northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Lebanese guerrilla group often fire Katyusha
rockets or mortar fire on Israel's border areas to retaliate the
killing or wounding of Lebanese civilians by Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
After the Hezbollah attack, Israeli fighter planes launched two
raids on suspected Hezbollah bases in the so-called security zone
in south Lebanon, which Israel set up in 1985 allegedly to protect
its northern area from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
This was the fourth time in the past six weeks that residents
in northern Israel had to take cover in bomb shelters.
</P>
<P>
The last time was at the beginning of the month when the
pro-Israeli militia South Lebanon Army withdrew from the Jezzine
enclave in south Lebanon, just outside the security zone.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak has pledged to withdraw
the Israeli army from southern Lebanon within a year. He has until
early next month to form a governing coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
