<HEADLINE> World Bank-Financed Poverty-Relief Project In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou Province
is using 19 million U.S. dollars in World Bank loans and 130
million yuan in other funds to plant 65,000 hectares of trees in a
bid to get rid of poverty there.
</P>
<P>
The endeavor is intended to benefit rural people living in
poverty and to promote economic development by improving the
environment. It is part of the World Bank's effort to help 12
underdeveloped provinces and autonomous regions in Central and
southwest China, based on an agreement signed by China and the
World Bank. The 12 areas will plant 545,000 hectares of trees and
establish 5 forest products processing enterprises within the next
4 years, using a total of 200 million U.S. dollars in World Bank
loans, in addition to local government funds.
</P>
<P>
When the Guizhou project is completed, its environment will be
improved and good economic results are expected, with 280,000
people removed from poverty, according to Ying Jianqiang, a senior
engineer in charge of the World Bank project there. He says that
the province will produce 6.4 million cubic meters more of timber
and 72,000 tons of dried and fresh fruits, worth 5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China has already planted 2.1 million hectares of trees with
World Bank's previous loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
