<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Wastes Generate Energy for Families in Rural South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region has 440,000 rural households using gas generated by animal
waste as fuel for cooking and lighting.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, this is six percent of the total
number of rural homes in this major agricultural area, which is
deficient in more conventional forms of energy like coal and oil.
</P>
<P>
Most of the region's inhabitants -- the Zhuang ethnic minority -
- used to have to scour the mountainsides in search of firewood
for cooking, but the wider use of new forms of energy like gas
generated from pig, sheep, and cow dung has brought the
destruction rate of forest resources down and has in effect
protected the environment of the region.
</P>
<P>
The regional government decided to build another 200,000 of
these gas ponds this year as a major public interest project.
</P>
<P>
China has 55 ethnic groups. The Zhuang have both the longest
history and largest population. Guangxi's more than 16 million
Zhuang live mostly in southern and central parts of the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
