<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern China Leads Nation In Test-Tube Babies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, is leading the country in test-tube
baby technology.
</P>
<P>
Zhuang Guanglun, the head of the Reproductive Medical Science
Center at Guangzhou's Zhongshan Medical University, says that they
have used the reproductive technology to assist 60 to 70 people
each month.
</P>
<P>
Zhongshan Medical University, Beijing Medical University's
Hospital No.3, and the Shanghai Ji'ai Genetics and IVF Institute --
China USA Center are China's three best-known test-tube baby
centers. Zhuang's center has produced more than 500 test-tube
babies since 1988, when China's first test-tube baby was born in
Beijing. The center has had a success rate of 30 percent. It has
also helped to make clinically healthy babies by selecting genes
without any hereditary diseases from an embryo to implant into a
woman's womb.
</P>
<P>
China's first test-tube baby, Zheng Mengzhu, is now 11 years
old. On March 10, 1998, she was invited to return from Gansu
Province to Beijing to celebrate her 10th birthday by Hospital No.
3, where she was born. The hospital has produced more than 200
test tube babies, with a success rate of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
A dozen hospitals in China have the service and have produced
about 1,000 test tube babies. The world's first test tube baby was
born in Britain in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
