<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 08:00 GMT, June 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav army troops and police forces finished
their pullout from the troubled southern province of Kosovo Sunday,
half a day ahead of the deadline defined in the June 10 United
Nations Security Council resolution to end the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO's Kosovo commander, Lieutenant-General Mike Jackson, in a
meeting with representatives of the Yugoslav and Serb governments
in the Kosovo provincial capital of Pristina, expressed his
satisfaction over the completion of withdrawal, according to news
reports reaching here.(Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- Coca Cola company here got blackmailed while its
problem of product contamination in Belgium and France had not
died, Berlin police said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The German newspaper Die Welt am Sonntag (Sunday World) quoted
police spokesman Hans-Eberhatdt-Schultz as saying that a
blackmailer E-mailed the company four weeks ago, asking it to
remit millions of marks to a certain bank account, or he would
poison its product. However, Schultz denied that this case had
anything to do with the recent Coca Cola product contamination in
France and Belgium.(Coca Cola-Blackmail)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- NATO and the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) reached
an agreement on the demilitarization of the separatist military
group in a mud-floored tent outside Pristina early Monday, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
British Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson, head of alliance forces in
Kosovo, and Hashim Thaci, KLA's political leader, signed the
agreement minutes after the midnight deadline. U.S. State
Department spokesman James Rubin witnessed the signing of the pact
in the tent, Jackson's headquarters.(Yugoslavia-NATO-KLA NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar Foreign Minister U Win Aung will pay an
official visit to Malaysia soon to further promote bilateral ties
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of his Malaysian counterpart Hamid Albar, U
Win Aung will pay the visit, according to an official
announcement here Monday.
</P>
<P>
This will be U Win Aung's another visit to a member country of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) after he toured
other ASEAN member countries in February and March this year.(
Myanmar-FM-Visit) 
</P>
