<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Township Enterprises in Northeast China Achieve Better Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Township enterprises in China's
Liaoning Province generated 112 billion yuan (13.6 billion U.S.
dollars) in output value at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Management and property rights restructuring have helped revive
a large number of enterprises, whose exports last year exceeded 28
billion yuan, up seven percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Gao Maoxin, the vice-head of township enterprise administration,
says that these enterprises have developed rapidly since the mid-
1980s because of their flexibility in decision making and
management, and greater competitiveness than large and medium-
sized state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
A series of new provincial government policies over the last
two years have further helped development. Statistics show that 30,
000 companies have been involved in the property rights
restructuring and that 2,800 have become share-holding companies.
</P>
<P>
Gao says that the reforms have also helped enterprises make
better use of tens of billions of yuan in idle assets and to get
nearly 4 billion yuan in funds and remove 5.8 billion yuan in
debts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
