<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Commerce Thrives in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The rapidly increasing number of
Internet users in China has paved the way for the introduction of
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
There were two million registered Internet users in China at
the end of 1998, and the number is estimated to rise to 20 million
by the year 2000, laying a good foundation for the development of
e-commerce in the country.
</P>
<P>
Electronic business activities, such as on-line ticketing,
shopping, banking and securities trading, as well as declaration
of dutiable goods, are gaining popularity among Chinese commercial
circles and ordinary residents.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of government departments have launched
websites on the Internet, in answer to the "Government-Online"
plans, which call for 60 percent of related departments to be
available on-line by the end of 1999, with the figure rising to 80
percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce is drawing increasing attention from the Chinese
government and the country's electronic-commerce framework is to
be publicized soon by an office under the Ministry of the
Information Industry.
</P>
<P>
East China's Zhejiang Province, one of the country's economic
giants, had 50,000 registered Internet users by the end of April,
with the figure growing by 20 percent annually. Some 80 percent of
Internet users in the province show interest in on-line shopping,
according to a recent survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
