<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Slashes Coal Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China produced 406.8 million tons
of coal in the first five months of the year, a fall of 6.52
percent from the same period last year, according to a report by
the State Administration of Coal Industry.
</P>
<P>
The reduced coal output, which accounts for 39.4 percent of
this year's 1.03-billion-ton target, is to respond to less demand
in the market. China's coal market is still overly saturated. By
the end of May, China had a stockpile of nearly 70 million tons of
coal.
</P>
<P>
Also by the end of last month, China closed down 23,168 coal
mines, which account for 89.8 percent of the total number of coal
mines to be shut down this year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the country will continue to eliminate
small coal mines, which are wasteful and pollutants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Archaeologists Find Palace Engineering Document </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have found
a book of documents on engineering for the Old Summer Palace,
which dates back 200 years, at a farmer's house in Yuanping County
in Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The Old Summer Palace (Yuan Ming Yuan) was built in Beijing in
the early Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) as an imperial garden and was
burned down by invading British and French forces in 1860.
</P>
<P>
The ten-volume hand-written collection has 429 pages and 120,
000 Chinese characters and provides a record of 5,800 engineering
projects for repair work on the Old Summer Palace and provides
valuable information about the Old Summer Palace and architecture
during the Qing Dynasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Wholesales Center In Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 21 (Xinhua)-- China is launching its first
wholesales commodity center in new Siberia according to a trade
official of the city of Jiamusi in Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The center now under construction in the city of Novosibirsk
will be the largest wholesales network exclusively for Chinese
goods in Siberia, the official says. Work on the 2,200-sq.m.
center is in its initial stage and is to be completed by the end
of August.
</P>
<P>
Over 30 Chinese enterprises, including some well-known big
firms across the country, have agreed to put their products there
and the Russian government has supported the project because many
Chinese goods are very popular within the Russians for their high
quality and relatively low price. Currently, the Siberian market
is flooded with goods from the United States, Britain, France,
Germany, Italy, and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The 34 million people in Novosibirsk and a large area around it
are potential buyers of Chinese products, the official says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
