<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air China Shows Gains in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Air China, the biggest airlines in
the country, reported gains in April and May this year after
recording serious losses in 1998, according to a responsible
official from the company.
</P>
<P>
 It is the first time this year that the company has said that
it made a profit, following reduction of losses in the first
quarter. The company did not disclose how much profit it had made
in the two months, but provide statistics that show the airlines'
passenger and freight turnover in April and May increasing 23.7
percent and 26.5 percent over the same period in 1998 and income
rising by 22.6 percent and 9.3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The freight turnover reached 534 million tons during January-
May, up 38.45 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
 China's civil aviation sector suffered from serious losses in
1998, due to the Asian financial crisis and its low efficiency. As
a result, the General Administration of Civil Aviation of China (
CAAC) vowed to turn those losses into a profit across the whole
sector this year.
</P>
<P>
 Ma Xulun, vice president of Air China, attributed the
positive result to the company's market-oriented efforts which
included strict control over costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
