<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 06:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freed Italians to Continue Work in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The three Italians recently freed
by Iranian abductors will continue their work in Iran, a
representative from their company Danieli said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The representative told reporters at Tehran airport that after
meeting their families, the Italians will return to their work in
the Alloy Steel Plant in Iran's central province of Yazd.
</P>
<P>
Lorenzo Termite, Giuseppe Zisa and Riccardo Pasinato arrived
in Tehran early Monday morning from Zahedan, capital of the
southeastern Sistan-Baluchestan province, which borders
Afghanistan and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the airport, Termite said
that he and his colleagues were freed around 13:00 local times
(0830 GMT) on Sunday after Iranian security forces reached an
agreement with the abductors.
</P>
<P>
The three Italians were taken captive on June 13 when they were
on a trip to see historical sites in Bam in the central province
of Kerman.
</P>
<P>
Termite believed that the abduction was pre-planned, saying
one of the six abductors called Reza said two of their men had
been jailed by Iranian authorities in Shiraz in southern Iran.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Italian engineer said the abductors first
introduced themselves as members of Taliban (the Afghan ruling
group), but later claimed they are Baluchis, the ethnic people
living in Sistan-Baluchestan province.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the press conference, Italian ambassador to
Iran Ludovico Ortona thanked Iranian authorities for taking
effective measures to set free the three Italian nationals.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of Iranian Interior Ministry Bahaoddin
Sheikholeslami announced Sunday that the Italians were freed
after a group of Iranian information and security personnel
entered into negotiation with the kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
But he gave no details about the negotiation and any possible
deal with the abductors.
</P>
<P>
He did not reveal the identities of the abductors and whether
they were arrested following the release of the Italians.
</P>
<P>
However, Governor General of the Sistan-Baluchestan province
Mahmoud Husseini told the Islamic Republic News Agency on Monday
that the abductors are bandits and drug smugglers.
</P>
<P>
He said that the abduction had no political motive, but "they
wanted to draw the attention of the government." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
