<HEADLINE> Brisk Sino-Nepanese Border Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A seven-year-old outdoor market in
the town of Zhangmu on the Sino-Nepalese border begins filling up
with Chinese and Nepalese business people haggling over prices
with the help of their electronic calculators even in the early
morning.
</P>
<P>
Because of geography and communications problems, the market
does not straddle the borderline but was located 8.7 kilometers
inside Chinese territory in Tibet, which Nepalese traders have to
cross the Friendship Bridge to reach.
</P>
<P>
According to an a Chinese and Nepalese government agreement,
people living within a 30-km. strip of the border are free to come
and go as they please. At the very beginning, the market only
operated on Saturdays, but it got so busy it had to open every day.
</P>
<P>
Chinese business people have over 50 shops dealing mainly in
electric goods, soaps, and shirts and the tax-free trade attracts
a lot of merchants from both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
Doing business here is worthwhile, Yin Yan, a Sichuan woman
said. The businesswomen sometimes can sell nearly 800 yuan worth
of goods a day.
</P>
<P>
There are on average 500 to 600 Nepalese business people coming
to the market each day and some Chinese have begun learning
Nepalese in their spare time because the language problem makes it
difficult to do business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
