<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway Beats Russia 2-1 in Women's World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Brit Sandaune and Marianne
Pettersen scored as Norway opened its defense of the Women's World
Cup title with a 2-1 win over Russia in a Group C match at Foxboro
Stadium, Massachusetts of the United States on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Norway improved to 11-2-0 all-time in the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Norway held a big offensive advantage against Russia, which was
making its World Cup debut. With the win, the Norwegians moved to
the top of the group, two points ahead of Japan and Canada that
tied 1-1 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm satisfied. I was pleased we created 19 good chances,"
Norway coach Per-Mathias Hogmo said. "It was a good win and we
will get better each day."
</P>
<P>
Norway opened the game with constant offensive pressure and
broke through in the 17th minute. Silke Jorgensen floated a cross
from the left side that was headed on by forward Pettersen.
Sanduane lifted a shot over the onrushing goalkeper Svetlana Petko
and into the net despite the best effort of defender Marina
Bourakova.
</P>
<P>
Norway held a clear advantage in the first half, outshooting
Russia 14-1 holding a 10-1 edge in corner kicks.
</P>
<P>
Pettersen was a danger all day in the offensive end and cashed
in one of her six shots in the 68th minute. A cross by Sandaune
was headed off Pettersen by Natalia Karesseva, but Pettersen
settled the ball and slipped it inside the left post.
</P>
<P>
"I thought we played OK," said Pettersen. "I hope we score more.
I'm happy I scored at least one goal."
</P>
<P>
Norway kept attacking, but the tactic backfired and allowed
Russia back in the game in the 77th minute. Irina Grigorieva ran
down a loose ball at the Norway touch line. Natalia Barbachina
settled the cross with her back to the goal and pushed a pass to
the edge of the penalty area, where Galina Komarova rocketed a
shot past goal keeper Bente Nordby into the top of the net.
</P>
<P>
"I'm satisfied with the match," Russia coach Yurii Bystrizkii
said. "I'm happy with the result. This was our first World Cup. We
are now focused on our next few games and our goal is to reach the
second round and finish second in our group."
</P>
<P>
The Russians were not able to come close to tying the game
after their goal.
</P>
<P>
Irina Gringorieva had three of the five second-half shots for
the Russians as they started to solve the Norweigan defense. She
forced Nordby to make her only save on a 35-yard shot.
</P>
<P>
"We were shaky in the back four," Hogmo added. "Russia was not
as close to us as the score would show. They were lucky to be in
it with us as long as they were."
</P>
<P>
Norway outhshot Russia 28-6 and forced Petko to make nine saves.
</P>
<P>
In another match played at Forxboro Stadium, Australia tied
Ghana 1-1 in Group D.
</P>
<P>
Australia opened the scoring in the 74th minute through Murray
Julie, but Ghana's Nana Gyamua tied the score two minutes later.
</P>
<P>
In their first appearance at an important international
tournament, Ghana's Black Queens impressed with a great fighting
spirit. Australia dominated the game from the start but failed to
capitalise when the African team was reduced to 10 after 26
minutes, needing 74 minutes to open the score.
</P>
<P>
Barikisu Tettey-Quao was sent out the field and four yellow
cards were flashed by American referee Kari Seitz in the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
