<HEADLINE> Venezuela Defeats Peru in Soccer Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Playing on home turf, Venezuela
scored three goals against nil in a soccer friendly against Peru
on Sunday, boosting its morale for the American Cup soccer
tournament next month.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time for Venezuela to beat Peru in the past
10 years as it only recorded two wins, two draws and 10 losses in
their previous 14 encounters.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, Venezuela had its last victory of 3-1 against Peru.
</P>
<P>
The first leg of the two-game friendly series was played in
Valencia, 150 kilometers away from Caracas, wherein the hosts
found the nets three times through Edson Tortolero, Jose Manuel
Rey and Fernando Orne Las in the 28th, 41st and 62nd minutes
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Coached by Argentine Jose Omar Pastoriza, Venezuela has
recently achieved promising progresses, including draws against
both Denmark and Colombia, double victories over Ecuador and a
tight loss against Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the match, the hosts resorted to active offenses
with speed through the midfield, but faced little pressure from
their counterparts who lacked cooperation in attacks and back-up
penetration.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the friendly was full of firepowers with rude actions from
both sides and furious protests against Venezuelan referee Paolo
Borbosano who fished out two red cards and six yellow cards.
</P>
<P>
The second friendly is slated on June 23rd in Lima, Peru,
before both sides will set off for Paraguay for the uncoming
American Cup soccer tournament from June 29 to July 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
