<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Endeavors in Combating Transnational Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A high ranking Myanmar official
Monday called for forging a common understanding among member
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
and making more effective endeavors in combating transnational
crime in the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony here Monday of the two-day
Senior Officials' Meeting of the Second ASEAN Ministerial Meeting
on Transnational Crime, Myanmar Minister of Home Affairs Colonel
Tin Hlaing disclosed that the issue on the establishment of the
ASEAN Center on Transnational Crime, an institutional framework on
ASEAN cooperation in combating transnational crime, will be
considered at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to formulate and implement an efficient
network among the national organizations concerned through the
formation of appropriate inter-agency committees and task forces
in individual member countries in order to enhance information
exchange on the transnational crime.
</P>
<P>
He called for seeking ways and means for obtaining technical
assistance and training equipment from ASEAN dialogue partners,
U.N. specialized agencies and other relevant international
organizations, having the view that information on the movements
and activities of transnational criminal organizations should be
exchanged with them.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the enhancement of regional security,
peace and prosperity, collaboration in combating such
transnational crimes as terrorism, drug trafficking, arms
smuggling, money laundering, trafficking in persons and piracy in
the region will be mainly on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The Senior Officials' Meeting will be followed by a Ministerial
Meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The First ASEAN Ministerial Meeting on Transnational Crime was
held in Manila, the Philippines on December 20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
