<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Chinese Put Environmental Responsibility on Government's Shoulders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A large number of Chinese people
regard environmental protection as the government's business, a
recent survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Conducted by the State Environmental Protection Administration
and the Ministry of Education, the survey lasted from July to
October 1998, investigating 9,202 samples from 31 provinces,
municipalities and regions nationwide, and covering the widest
range and largest number of samples of any survey of its kind.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that the general public recognizes that China
has a serious environmental pollution problem -- water and air
pollution being the people's major concerns. The survey also shows
that educational level is the dominant factor deciding the public'
s environmental awareness.
</P>
<P>
The survey concluded that it is due to the government-dominated
pattern of China's environmental protection that the public's
environmental awareness tends to be government-oriented.
</P>
<P>
The general public has no clear idea of what it should and can
do for environmental protection, according to the survey. People
are more concerned about environmental problems closely related to
their own daily lives and what the government is doing to solve
their problems than about the environment far away from them,
according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
As for the relationship between economic development and
environmental protection, the survey found that public opinion
tends to prioritize the former. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
