<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, June 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- The World Bank will continue to assist
Tanzania in solving the debt problem so that the country's economy
could develop at a faster pace, a senior bank official said here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Although Tanzania did not get debt relief at a G-8 summit in
Germany earlier this week, the country does have a debt problem,
World Bank Managing Director and Corporate Secretary Shengman
Zhang told Xinhua. (Tanzania-WB Debt)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said Sunday that
Italy's deficit would be lowered to 1.5 percent of GDP by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency ANSA, D'Alema, who is being
present at the Group of Eight economic summit in Cologne of
Germany, said that the deficit target would be reached through a
combination of spending cuts and the easing of Italy's high level
of fiscal pressure, adding that the government was committed to
lowering the amount of taxes paid by low-income families. (Italy-
Economy-Deficit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam's key economic region in the south of the
country has recorded relatively high growth in industrial output
of between 8.2 and 29 percent since early this year, Vietnam's
English daily Vietnam News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The region includes Ho Chi Minh City and the southern provinces
of Dong Nai, Binh Duong and Ba Ria-Vung Tau. With 29,000
industrial production establishments and 33 industrial parks (IPs)
and export processing zones (EPZs), the total industrial output
value of the key economic region equals two-thirds of all
production in southern Vietnam and half of the entire country. (
Vietnam-Economy)
</P>
