<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agricultural Minister Urges Better Crop Mix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China is set to optimize its crop
mix to upgrade grain quality in the face of mounting grain
reserves and an expected bumper summer harvest, according to the
Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Agriculture Chen Yaobang was quoted by Monday's
China Daily as saying that cutting down the acreage growing
inferior strains and expanding production of high-grade grain and
cotton have been listed as the ministry's top priorities.
</P>
<P>
Years of bumper harvests and a continuous emphasis on quantity
by the government have created large stockpiles of grain and
cotton, which are believed to have outstripped market demand, said
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Growing areas for grain strains of low quality, including
Spring wheat crops in northeast China and indica rice in south
China, will be cut substantially, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"The agricultural departments nationwide should work out a crop-
growing mix readjustment program compatible with local natural,
economic and technological conditions," the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed promotion of high-quality crops and marketable
cash crops through supply of fine seed strains and introduction of
modern technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Key Economic Region Records High Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's key economic region in the
south of the country has recorded relatively high growth in
industrial output of between 8.2 and 29 percent since early this
year, Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The region includes Ho Chi Minh City and the southern provinces
of Dong Nai, Binh Duong and Ba Ria-Vung Tau. With 29,000
industrial production establishments and 33 industrial parks (IPs)
and export processing zones (EPZs), the total industrial output
value of the key economic region equals two-thirds of all
production in southern Vietnam and half of the entire country.
</P>
<P>
Despite the negative influence caused by the regional economic
crisis, the region was able to increase their industrial output
last year, with growth rates of between 11 and 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dong Nai province, the location of nine major IPs, registered
an increase of 16 percent in industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Binh Duong province has recorded an increase of 9.7 percent in
industrial output so far this year, with foreign-invested
enterprises registering a 29 percent increase over the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum and power industries are dominant in Ba Ria-Vung Tau
province where extraction of crude oil is expected to top 14.5
million tons and production of gas to reach 1.2 billion cubic
meters this year.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City is the largest component of the key economic
region. In the first four months of the year, the city's
industrial production increased 8.2 percent over the same period
last year. However, the city's industrial growth is the lowest in
the past several years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Major Events Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Following is a chronology of major
events over the troubled Yugoslav province of Kosovo since early
this year.
</P>
<P>
January 29 -- The six-nation Contact Group meeting in London
summons the warring Serbs and ethnic Albanians to attend peace
talks in Rambouillet, near Paris, on February 6, in order to end
an 11-month violence in Kosovo. The U.N. Security Council voices
support for the decision to seek negotiated political settlement
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
February 6 -- The peace talks are opened by host French
President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
February 14 -- The Contact Group extends talks until February
20.
</P>
<P>
February 18 -- NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana threatens
to launch air strikes against Serbian targets if the talks fail.
</P>
<P>
February 20 -- The Contact Group extends the talks until
February 23.
</P>
<P>
February 21 -- Yugoslav army chief General Dragoljub Djdanic
vows to defend Kosovo "at all costs."
</P>
<P>
February 23 -- Major powers say a partial peace agreement is
reached and the two sides will meet again in France on March 15 to
implement the accord.
</P>
<P>
March 15 -- Peace talks resume in Paris. No deadline is given.
</P>
<P>
March 18 -- Kosovo Albanians sign the draft peace agreement on
autonomy in Paris unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
March 19 -- The Contact Group adjourns peace talks, warning
they will not reopen unless Belgrade accepts the autonomy accord.
The breakdown of the peace talks plunges Kosovo into a darker
perspective of bloodshed and war, and increases the risk of NATO
military intervention. Western countries begin to evacuate
diplomatic staffs and their dependents in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
March 20 -- Some 1,400 cease-fire verifiers from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe withdraw from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
March 22 -- U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke arrives in Belgrade in
a last-ditch bid to persuade Milosevic to accept the accord.
</P>
<P>
March 23 -- Holbrooke makes no breakthrough after meeting twice
with Milosevic. Solana orders air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
March 24 -- NATO launches air war against Yugoslav targets.
</P>
<P>
March 27 -- Intense NATO bombardments cause massive refugee
exodus from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
April 1 -- Yugoslav television shows three U.S. soldiers
captured near Yugoslav-Macedonian border. Yugoslavia frees the
three soldiers on May 2 after a visit by U.S. civil rights leader
Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
April 3 -- NATO missiles destroy Yugoslav ministries in first
strikes on central Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
April 14 -- NATO air strikes hit ethnic Albanian refugees in
Kosovo road convoys. Yugoslavia reports 64 dead. NATO admits it
has made mistakes five days later.
</P>
<P>
April 21 -- NATO blasts headquarters of President Slobodan
Milosevic's Socialist Party of Serbia and his private residence in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
April 23 -- NATO attacks Serbian state television building in
central Belgrade, killing at least 10 people.
</P>
<P>
May 2 -- NATO graphite bombs short-circuit Yugoslav power grid.
</P>
<P>
May 7 -- NATO attacks Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, killing
three Chinese journalists and wounding many.
</P>
<P>
May 13 -- NATO bombs Kosovo village of Korisa, killing 87
ethnic Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
May 22 -- NATO bombs army barracks at Kosare which were
captured by Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
May 23 -- NATO begins intensive bombing of Yugoslav electricity
grid, causing major disruption of power and water supplies.
</P>
<P>
May 29 -- Two Australian aid workers and a Yugoslav colleague
are convicted in Belgrade of spying and jailed.
</P>
<P>
May 30 -- NATO aircraft bomb crowded bridge in Varvarin,
central Serbia, killing nine people and injuring at least 17.
</P>
<P>
June 3 -- Yugoslavia accepts peace plan brought to Belgrade by
European Union and Russian envoys requiring withdrawal of all
forces from Kosovo and entry of peacekeepers under U.N. mandate.
</P>
<P>
June 8 -- The West and Russia, at G8 foreign ministers' meeting
in Cologne, Germany, agree wording for U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
June 9 -- NATO and Yugoslav military commanders agree on timing,
details of Yugoslav withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
June 10 -- Serb forces start withdrawal from Kosovo; NATO
suspends air war; U.N. Security Council endorses peace terms.
</P>
<P>
June 11 -- About 200 Russian peacekeepers enter Kosovo from
Bosnia, taking NATO by surprise.
</P>
<P>
June 12 -- NATO troops enter Kosovo at dawn, British first
followed by French and Americans; Russian peacekeepers take
control of the Pristina airport.
</P>
<P>
June 14 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees start to return home to
Kosovo; Serb refugees pour out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
June 15 -- The International Committee of the Red Cross says at
least 33,000 ethnic Serbs have fled Kosovo since the weekend for
fear of reprisals from ethnic Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
June 18 -- U.S. and Russian defense ministers agree in Helsinki
that Russian peacekeepers will not have a separate sector in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
June 19 -- Three Serb civilians are killed in a shoot-out with
Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) separatists near Pec as Italian
peacekeeping troops try to disarm the guerrillas. The commander of
the Italian contingent, General Mauro Del Vecchio, banned the KLA
from walking in the town armed and in uniform the previous day.
</P>
<P>
June 20 -- Yugoslav army troops and police forces finish their
pullout from Kosovo, half a day ahead of the deadline. NATO
announces official end to air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
June 21 -- NATO and the KLA reach an agreement on the
demilitarization of the separatist military group in a mud-floored
tent outside Pristina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
