<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Public Condemns Doctors' Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A week long strike since last
Monday by Sri Lanka's government doctors has been severely
condemned by the public who have been greatly inconvenienced.
</P>
<P>
The public wants the government to take stern action against
the doctors who were educated with public funds and whose salaries
are being paid for by the public, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of patients have been turned away from state
hospitals since June 14 as about 4,500 doctors of the Government
Medical Officers Association (GMOA) began an indefinite strike.
</P>
<P>
A retired government doctor condemned the strike as being
totally unethical and a disgrace to the profession.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA leadership were accused of trying to boost their ego
through strike action at the expense of hundreds of thousands of
the poor, most of them villagers who could ill-afford to pay
private medical bills.
</P>
<P>
Hospital authorities said only emergency services were
functioning at hundreds of state-run hospitals across Sri Lanka
while other routine operations and services had been rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA called the strike in protest against a court petition
filed by the chief minister of the North Western Provincial
Council, who wants provincial control over health services.
</P>
<P>
All appointments, transfers and other official matters are
currently decided by the central government's Public Service
Commission.
</P>
<P>
A GMOA spokesman said Sunday that they will continue their
strike defying a Presidential Essential Service Order, until the
government gives a firm assurance that the problem that initiated
their action will be solved.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka provides free health services to its citizens, but
state hospitals are overcrowded and those who can afford it seek
treatment at private hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
