<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Elephants Killed By Power Lines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Four wild elephants were
electrocuted in Sri Lanka's jungles off Batticalao in the East
when they crashed into high tension power lines that were sagging,
reports reaching here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the power lines had been sagging due to
sabotage by the Tamil rebels who had blown up electricity pylons
in the area. The rebels have been fighting for a separate state in
the country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Electricity Board workmen had, however, had not repaired the
lines but made only ad hoc arrangements which proved fatal for the
elephants.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that a young male elephant had first got
electrocuted and the other three would have gone to its rescue and
got electrocuted themselves. 
</P>
