<HEADLINE> Tibetans Enjoy Complete Religious Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- "Tibetan Buddhist believers enjoy
complete freedom of religious belief," said Bomi Kamdalozhub, a
vice-chairman of the China Buddhist Association (CBA).
</P>
<P>
The 80-year old Living Buddha, who is also chairman of the CBA'
s branch in the Tibet Autonomous Region, told Xinhua that the
government's policies on religions have been thoroughly
implemented in Tibet over the past decades.
</P>
<P>
According to the Buddhist leader, the central and regional
governments have invested over 300 million yuan in repairing and
maintaining temples and other religious sites in Tibet in the past
two decades.
</P>
<P>
So far, 1,787 temples and religious sites have been built or
repaired, over 300 more than those in 1959, when the democratic
reform was initiated in Tibet. Furthermore, all the major festival
activities of Tibetans have been restored and are now held on a
larger scale than before.
</P>
<P>
The government has issued a series of regulations to protect
religious places and relics, while over the past two decades alone
over 55 million yuan has been allocated to restore and repair
religious relics. In 1984, a printing house was set up specially
to print Buddhist scriptures in the Tibetan language.
</P>
<P>
The Living Buddha, who chaired the lot-drawing ceremony on
November 29, 1995 to select the 11th Panchen Lama, also noted that
the selection was carried out strictly in line with religious
rules and practices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
