<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Forces Finish Pullout From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav army troops and police
forces finished their pullout from the troubled southern province
of Kosovo Sunday, half a day ahead of the deadline defined in the
June 10 United Nations Security Council resolution to end the
crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO's Kosovo commander, Lieutenant-General Mike Jackson, in a
meeting with representatives of the Yugoslav and Serb governments
in the Kosovo provincial capital of Pristina, expressed his
satisfaction over the completion of withdrawal, according to news
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting with Jackson also on Sunday, Yugoslav
deputy foreign minister Nebojsa Vujovic expressed the hope that
the United Nations peacekeeping forces in Kosovo could fully
assume the responsibility for protecting the safety of life and
property of all the ethnic groups in Kosovo after the withdrawal
of Yugoslav army troops and police forces.
</P>
<P>
Vujovic expressed his disappointment over the peacekeeping
forces' failure to stop a large number of Albanian nationals from
illegally entering Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
According to him, these Albanian nationals, after illegally
crossing into Kosovo, were engaged in criminal activities such as
looting, threatening the safety of all ethnic groups, including
ethnic Kosovo Albanians, in the province.
</P>
<P>
Vujovic demanded that Jackson order a closure of the Yugoslavia-
Albania border and repatriate the Albanian aliens back into their
own country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
