<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, KLA Sign Demilitarization Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 21 (Xinhua) -- NATO and the Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA) reached an agreement on the demilitarization of the
separatist military group in a mud-floored tent outside Pristina
early Monday, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
British Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson, head of alliance forces in
Kosovo, and Hashim Thaci, KLA's political leader, signed the
agreement minutes after the midnight deadline. U.S. State
Department spokesman James Rubin witnessed the signing of the pact
in the tent, Jackson's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Under the demilitarization agreement, KLA separatists must turn
over heavy weapons and stop carrying weapons in many parts of
Kosovo. Anything bigger than a sidearm or hunting rifle must be
placed in storage within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also urges the separatists to maintain a cease-
fire, dismiss all foreign members and respect the peacekeepers'
authority on security matters.
</P>
<P>
However, violent attacks against Serb citizens were frequently
reported in Kosovo as the Yugoslav troops pulled out.
</P>
<P>
The independent Beta news agency reported that a group of
Kosovo Albanians looted and set fire to 20 Serb houses on Sunday
in the village of Grace, near Pristina. On Sunday afternoon, an
explosive blew up in a campus of Pristina University, British
troops said.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Kosovo Serbs, fearing the departure of the
Serbian troops will leave them vulnerable to KLA separatist
attacks, have fled Kosovo so far.
</P>
<P>
Late Sunday, one person was killed in a shooting in the
Pristina suburb of Dardanija, Beta reported, quoting witnesses as
saying the gunfire lasted about 10 minutes before peacekeepers
arrived on the scene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
