<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Archaeologists Find Palace Engineering Document </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have found
a book of documents on engineering for the Old Summer Palace,
which dates back 200 years, at a farmer's house in Yuanping County
in Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The Old Summer Palace (Yuan Ming Yuan) was built in Beijing in
the early Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) as an imperial garden and was
burned down by invading British and French forces in 1860.
</P>
<P>
The ten-volume hand-written collection has 429 pages and 120,
000 Chinese characters and provides a record of 5,800 engineering
projects for repair work on the Old Summer Palace and provides
valuable information about the Old Summer Palace and architecture
during the Qing Dynasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
