<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafter Wins Heineken Trophy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Patrick Rafter waited five hours
and came from a first-set deficit to win the Heineken Trophy grass
court title in Den Bosch, the Netherlands on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian world No. 2 retained his ATP Heineken title with
a hard win of 3-6, 7-6 (9-7) and 6-4 over unseeded Romanian Andrei
Pavel after the rain delayed the competition for five hours.
</P>
<P>
Despite the miserable conditions, both players performed a
competitive but good-natured duel to entertain the patient crowd.
</P>
<P>
Pavel, who ranked 66th in the world, took the first set by
breaking Rafter's serve in the eighth game.
</P>
<P>
Rafter had to save a match point at 6-5 down in the second-set
tiebreaker, but after that never looked back.
</P>
<P>
Stepping up a gear and playing almost faultless tennis, Rafter
broke twice in the final set to take a 5-1 lead. Pavel came back
to 5-4 but the end was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
The play had begun almost at the last possible moment as both
players were waiting to be whisked away by helicopter to London,
where Rafter is seeded No.2 and Pavel is scheduled to play a first-
round match against Andre Agassi on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
