<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, June 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain said on Sunday that last year's landmark
peace deal for Northern Ireland could unravel over the summer if
parties fail to bury the hatchet this month.
</P>
<P>
Pro-British Protestant and Irish nationalist Roman Catholic
political leaders face a June 30 deadline to seal the peace as
negotiating deadlock and a rise in street violence threaten a
return of the "Troubles" that reigned for three decades. (
NIreland-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan expressed its satisfaction at the G-8
statement on the situation in Kashmir in a press release issued by
the Foreign Office late Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, the G-8 has expressed its deep
concern on the continuing military confrontation in Kashmir and
has called for an end to military action as well as respect for
the Line of Control (LoC) by both India and Pakistan. (Pakistan-G-
8-Kashmir)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- NATO Secretary General Javier Solana announced here
on Sunday the formal end to NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Solana told reporters that he made this announcement after
receiving a report from the NATO military authorities about the
complete withdrawal of Yugoslav forces from Kosovo. (NATO-
Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOGNE -- The United States President Bill Clinton and his
Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin on Sunday agreed to resume their
talks for the third stage treaty of restricting atom weaponry (
Start III).
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed to hold further talks over the
change to Anti Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty to confine the anti-
missile defensive system. The talks seemed more necessary after
the U.S. planned to develop its new anti-missile system. (US-
Russia-Nuclear)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The Japanese government will actively take part in the
stability process of the Balkan region, said Japan Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi on Sunday after the European Union (EU) and Japan
summit in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo is ready to help the Kosovar refugees as part of its duty
for peace and stability in Europe, said a joint statement issued
by the Bonn chancellery after the meeting. (Japan-Balkan)
</P>
</TEXT>
