<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Satisfied With G-8 Statement on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan expressed its
satisfaction at the G-8 statement on the situation in Kashmir in a
press release issued by the Foreign Office late Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, the G-8 has expressed its deep
concern on the continuing military confrontation in Kashmir and
has called for an end to military action as well as respect for
the Line of Control (LoC) by both India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 has also called for the resumption of the dialogue
between the two South Asian countries in the spirit of the Lahore
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
This amounts to "virtual endorsement of Pakistan's stand" which
it had taken at the foreign minister meeting in New Delhi on June
12, 1999, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
"India's rejection of the dialogue process has been clearly not
acceptable," observed the release. "Pakistan's stand that the
hostilities in Kashmir should be halted, the LoC mutually
respected and the dialogue resumed for a peaceful solution has
been upheld by the G-8 Summit leaders."
</P>
<P>
The press release also urged the international community to
"engage itself in facilitating the resumption of the dialogue
between India and Pakistan for a final settlement of the Kashmir
dispute."
</P>
<P>
Since early May, Pakistan and India have been engaged in an
intensifying artillery dual across the LoC in the disputed
Himalayan region of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz paid a visit to New
Delhi on June 12, in a bid to defuse the tension between the two
countries, but his talks with his Indian counterpart Jaswant Singh
ended fruitlessly, after which India declared to continue its
military strikes against Muslim fighters in India-held Kashmir who
were claimed to have infiltrated from the Pakistani side.
</P>
<P>
In order to seek international sympathy, Pakistan has sent its
ambassador to the United Nations, Munir Akram, as the special
envoy to the G-8 Summit in Cologne, Germany, to brief the G-8
leaders on the latest developments in Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990621.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria, Republic of Congo Qualify for 2000 African Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Both Algeria and the Republic of
Congo scored the last-day wins to qualify for the 2000 African Cup
of Nations finals on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As Ivory Coast and Togo also advance for the 16-nation field,
one berth remains to be decided from a three-team league playoff
between Zimbabwe, Eritrea and Senegal.
</P>
<P>
Algeria beat Uganda 2-0 to take the second berth from Group 7
while the Republic of Congo beat Namibia 3-0 to finish runner-up
in Group 3.
</P>
<P>
Ivory Coast won Group 3 despite a lackluster 0-0 draw with Mali,
while Togo, which lost to Guinea 2-1 in Conakry, went through on
goal differential after Morocco won the group previously.
</P>
<P>
Besides Morocco, other teams that have secured their places
were Cameroon, South Africa, Gabon, Burkina Faso, Zambia, Congo
and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
They will join defending champion Egypt and co-hosts Nigeria
and Ghana in next year's finals.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Eritrea beat Mozambique 1-0 to claim its place in
the playoff, and Senegal topped Burundi 1-0 to likewise earn its
second chance at qualifying for the finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
