<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Peace Faces 10-Day Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Sunday that last
year's landmark peace deal for Northern Ireland could unravel over
the summer if parties fail to bury the hatchet this month.
</P>
<P>
Pro-British Protestant and Irish nationalist Roman Catholic
political leaders face a June 30 deadline to seal the peace as
negotiating deadlock and a rise in street violence threaten a
return of the "Troubles" that reigned for three decades.
</P>
<P>
UK's Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam warned both sides
they must resolve their differences in 10 days -- or else.
</P>
<P>
"They've both got to take their blinkers off, take risks and go
forward. Now it isn't going to be easy but unless we get something
in place, it (peace) will slowly unravel I believe over the
summer," Mowlam told BBC television.
</P>
<P>
"We have 10 days...We can do it if we try," she said.
</P>
<P>
The impasse centres on the surrender of guerrilla weapons and
has stalled the creation of a new all-party executive, elected
last year.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who helped broker the
so-called Good Friday accord, has cleared his diary for the final
days of June, aiming to harry the British-ruled province into a
long-awaited peace, according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton, who has intervened directly in
previous phases of negotiation, has told Blair that he too is
ready to do anything he can to help.
</P>
<P>
"We couldn't ask for a better situation and the 30th deadline,
I think, is a clear focus," Mowlam was quoted saying.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Blair, his Irish counterpart Bertie
Ahern and a range of Protestant and Catholic parties in April
1998, has stalled over demands for Irish Republican Army (IRA)
guerrillas to disarm.
</P>
<P>
A series of talks led by Blair and Ahern have so far failed to
bridge the gulf between David Trimble, the province's "unionist"
first minister, and Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political arm.
</P>
<P>
Trimble refuses to form a coalition cabinet that would include
Sinn Fein until the IRA hands in weapons that fuelled a 30-year
onslaught against British rule.
</P>
<P>
Blair visited Belfast last week and is expecting to go again
and take part personally in talks as the deadline approaches.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Britain's Sky News television, Blair
admitted it would be "very difficult indeed" to meet the deadline,
but said the alternative was too grim to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
"There's a whole generation of young people in Northern Ireland
for whom this is the last chance," Blair said. "I don't believe we
will be forgiven if we can't do it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
